author: Eddie Avinashi
text:
This movie is mesmerizing in it's own right. But I'd argue, regardless of quality, it's arguably one of the most IMPORTANT films made this century.

Not only does it coincide with the War in Ukraine, which is igniting everyone's fears of Nuclear utilization, it also coincides with a moment in history where more and more people are thinking about the existential security of the human race. The debate over things like Climate Change and Artificial Intelligence is hotter than ever and, for the latter subject, it is also advancing at an increasingly faster rate with things like ChatGPT and Bard.

Oppenheimer wrestles with the complex morality of being the very inception of a thing that, in some future timeline, has the potential to destroy all of humanity. Is it ethical to delve into the fabric of scientific truth to do this? Even if one doesn't wield it to destroy, are they accountable for it's creation?

The same question can be said about Artificial Intelligence. If it becomes sentient or superintelligent and/or used for harm, are it's creators accountable? If we were all wiped out, would it even matter?

author: All Things Wealth
text: Went to see this recently. Man...... the visuals and the cerebral feelings throughout using music and sound FX were just a work of art. Huge props to the visual effects, the costume designers, the music supervisors, and of course the directing. Creating a movie where many people already know the outcome is always a little bit harder. The immediate thought is, "I know what the outcome of the atomic bomb was". But to recreate the events in a way that makes you wonder what might happen next, as well as capturing the manic/genius side of Robert Oppenheimer throughout was a piece of movie-making genius. It's one of those movies film schools will definitely reference when teaching people how to add emotion to various scenes.

author: KINGHALO
text: Someone said this movie blew him away.  I thought it just plain old blew.  So GD wordy and over-rehearsed.  40% of the mumbles and slurring and accents were inaudible in the iMax theater.  Cillian killed it.  And I wanted to ‚Äúkill myself‚Äù.  It was a 60 minute documentary dragged out into a way-too-long of a discombobulatedly-edited Nolan classic pushing the limits of story telling where Dumbkirk and Tenet come together to make one of his worst pieces of shit yet.  Beautifully shot.  Music unrelentingly drowns us with provoked emotion that doesn‚Äôt fit many of the scenes a sex scene showing sexual nudity in a completely class less fashion and impertinent in every way to the story and stride of this movie.  I was glued to the screen about 3 times.  The bomb blast was interesting.  And the ending had me actually forgetting about the items I forgot to add to my shopping list for afterwards.  Circumlocutive story telling wrapped up in an over-priced package filled with chaos and big blue psychopath-staring eyes and high cheek bones so prominent that one can‚Äôt help but be distracted.  Hahaha.  Total disappointment, even though I was impressed with cinematography and some acting.  Almost walked out from boredom and the inability understand inarticulable mumblings of Downey and several others.  Maybe it was just the iMax theater audio.  Two middle fingers up for this one!

author: Video Prod.
text:
Don't believe what Christopher Nolan says.
"On Oppenheimer film"

Thus, Universal and Christopher Nolan excluded over 80% of the film‚Äôs vfx crew from the credits. Why? Who knows. It certainly wasn‚Äôt a running time issue. At three hours in length, an additional 10 seconds of credits wouldn‚Äôt have made a bit of difference to the audience. But it would have meant the world to the workers who could have had a screen credit on a blockbuster film. (It‚Äôs telling that many of the workers who were left out of the credits worked at one of DNEG‚Äôs facilities in India.)

Not crediting the vfx crew is actually fairly common practice in Hollywood, and because vfx artists aren‚Äôt unionized, there is no recourse for the worker and no penalty for the studio when credits are omitted or misrepresented.

In a day and age when literally everyone connected to a film production gets a credit, from craft services to on-set teachers of child actors to random ‚Äúproduction babies‚Äù who didn‚Äôt even work on a film, it is utterly incomprehensible that vfx artists, whose work makes possible the final images that appear onscreen, are routinely omitted from screen credits.

Oppenheimer¬†is yet another example of how live-action filmmakers like Nolan denigrate and misrepresent the work of vfx workers to the media, and then add insult to injury by not even acknowledging them in the credits. The fact that over 125 people who contributed to¬†Oppenheimer‚Äôs success aren‚Äôt listed in the credits is a reminder of how the vfx industry is a corrupt and broken enterprise that undermines and disrespects its workers at every juncture.

This piece was updated on July 25 with additional information from DNEG about the use of vfx in the film.

author: SuperSunnymax
text:
A review from my brother
"I have not sat down to write a review in a long time, but watched Oppenheimer on the big screen today and I was left speechless. Cinematic senses dulled by unfocused ott content and superhero brainlessness were brought alive by the scorching fire of an atomic bomb detonated close to eight decades ago, the vision of one Cristopher Nolan and the understated craftsmanship of that reclusive Irishman - Cillian Murphy.

To begin a string of complements on this film would do injustice to the beautiful non linear narration that has you gripped every second of its three hour duration. Not once did it feel dragging, if anything it only deserved more screen time to explore certain unanswerable aspects of human psyche, values and moral scruples. But unlike most of his movies in which time and space are near tangible characters that are twisted and broken between which people are placed to further the story, in Oppenheimer, Nolan uses non linear narration as a tool for his fetish with time ( the last scene completes the assembly of narrative), but the story, strength and soul of the movie are very much human.

Without making a demi god of the men who split the atom and worked with nuclear fusion and fission, and pilfering hard reality in sentimentality, the movie lays them bare as men with deep and irreparable flaws. None more so than the titular character. As with many great men and women through the pages of history, his values change colour and mutate in matters of personal life but remain steadfast and unmoving in their work and creation. And Cillian Murphy used that to add so much depth and soul to play his character, that one forgets his uncanny resemblance to the real Oppenheimer.
Undoubtedly his best scenes are during his interrogation in the grey room by Jason Clarke. Those moments of silence of dejection, of a man facing defeat despite having achieved so much..he lived those moments.

There is a behind the scenes footage of one of his early films, before he was such a big star, where the director can be heard talking to Murphy in a rather harsh manner to do as he is told basically, and Murphy in his quiet voice saying ‚ÄúI was just trying the line this way.‚Äù That‚Äôs always stuck with me as I became a huge fan of his work. How he has turned into one of the finest actors of his generation without losing himself to the strappings of stardom. There is a power to his screen presence that lends a brevity to any scene he is in, which few can lay claim to today.

The movie is literally a star studded feast, with everyone doing their part to perfection (bravo again to Nolan). Robert Downey Jr, understated, and cold when he has to be with his sheer talent got himself out of being straightjacketed into the ‚ÄòI am Iron man‚Äô clich√©. The list is endless, with even bit roles played by some of the best artists in the industry such as Rami Malek, Kenneth Brannagh, Casey Affleck, and Gary Oldman sizzling his five minutes on screen as president Truman. But none of them rob the movie of it‚Äôs story or narration, and that is again the power of the story and direction of Nolan.
One character worth mentioning in the movie is Kitty, Oppenheimer‚Äôs wife played by one of my favourite actresses Emily blunt. In the whole story, where men draw rules, break them and scurry to work behind shadows, her character arc is one of a different sort of strength and though she is by no means perfect she could perhaps be an example for others to look up to.

Credit for the soul of the movie as with many good films lies in the music score. With another fantastic work by Ludwig Goransonn. If the background score is vaguely familiar then do go back to Shuri‚Äôs entrance as black panther, dropping out of her aircraft onto MBaku‚Äôs hall, in Wakanda Forever.
That score gave that moment such emotional depth..that's the power of a good bgm. It is the same monastic gong that moves hauntingly through the more poignant parts of the film. He has a knack for haunting melodies, the end credits of the Mandalorian can be rewatched over and over just to see the artwork with that score.

That this is a movie for today‚Äôs world is a given. But it‚Äôs core theme, the consequences to one‚Äôs violent actions (directly or indirectly), and how one continues to perform such a task, and deal with it subsequently have been explored long, long before. It was not without reason that Oppenheimer would fall back to that very quote from the gita, that text itself originating along a similar dilemma of wartime soul searching. But those are philosophical aspects of the movie which are best discussed with a drink in hand and a friend who has nothing better to talk about.

For now.. salute to one of the finest movies seen in recent years."

author: 127 H
text:
In golden robes, the sun ascends the sky,
A herald of hope, its light brushed on high.
With every ray, a promise to unfold,
A tapestry of life, in hues of gold.

It kisses blooms awake with tender grace,
And paints the world anew, a wondrous place.
Its warmth ignites the embers of our souls,
Igniting dreams, rekindling forgotten goals.

Yet, as the sun does shine with brilliant might,
A shadow looms, a darker, grimmer sight.
In mankind's hands, a power so profound,
The atom's wrath, where devastation's found.

We wield the force, destruction's bitter seed,
A choice that stains the earth with sorrow's greed.
With fiery blooms that sear and scar the land,
We mar creation with our heedless hand.

Oh, sun that rises, beacon in the sky,
Your light brings life, while hope and dreams arise.
May we, as stewards of this fragile earth,
Choose paths of peace, of love and second birth.

Let not the power that's given to our hands,
Be used to wield destruction's deadly brands.
Instead, let's strive to mend and heal the pain,
And let compassion's light our world regain.

For as the sun does rise and grace the morn,
Let's rise above the darkness that was born.
In unity, let's strive for life's embrace,
And let the sun's hope shine on every face.

author: Amogh
text: Just hopped in here to watch this trailer again was like 2 weeks ago I watched this masterpiece on a whole big screen and obviously for me was nolan's first movie to experience on big screen never knew I would get so much intense chills even tho I didn't got to watch in imax kinda regret that but still on normal screen it was damn overwhelming as well.. every particular scene holds that deeper meaning which makes totally our mind think for every seconds especially each and every character's mind games they play over and deep serious background music in every scene is what really made it more inquisitive yeah the plot represents about history, chemistry, politics but more in a interesting way that attracts deeper attention within.. we all do imagine a lot of stuff being inside our head thoughts which creates that imagination and the way he keeps on imagining the big bang I also really felt that similarity in me coz I'm also like a thinker and one who imagines a lot all the time living inside head.. one of the most trembling scene obviously was the explosion just like "light travels faster than sound" wasn't able to take my eyes off from such a giant fireball everything went dead silence for seconds but when the sound blasted in felt like a heavy strike on my face just like Ali's power cross  yeah and I shooked little pulled back into layed position on seat tremendous feeling tho.. horrifying scenes as well was literally shivering and ending scene felt me with absolute mesmerism of about the calculations and chain reaction.. first time hearing the music "can you hear the music" lured up my mind with such a enticement that I'm still constantly obsessed with it and did felt some imagination and connection in my head through that music.. but truly I enjoyed it all.. tears, emotion, intense feeling, terror, dark reality, imagination is like what i got the actual feel from it and don't know if I could ever get this type of  feeling experience from any other movie

author: Neal Fager
text:
I don't believe there is any meaning to life other than what we each give it ourselves but some moments and movies are so good they feel extremely important.

This movie is as moving powerful and feels as important or like it was meant to be made more than almost any I've ever seen.

If this movie doesn't shake you to your core, literally and figuratively, because the background music and sound editing is so good it felt like the theater was shaking, then you don't have a core.

I immediately put this in the top 3 most powerful or moving movies I've ever seen with Schindler's List and The Shawshank Redemption and while I haven't watched SL much because it's so dark and disturbing it's obviously hauntingly good and I've watched
The SR so many times I couldn't possibly count them.

But if it doesn't win many awards something is seriously wrong with those who vote for the Oscars or Golden Globes or any other awards.

I'd go with at least 10 awards just off the top of my head!

author: Chakriya Son
text:
Oppenheimer was great for many reasons. For one, I really like the dialogues. But we‚Äôll get to the reasons that make it a great film in its own league later. Now Oppenheimer. What is it really? A biopic? A documentary? It‚Äôs many things. I‚Äôd say it‚Äôs a docudrama (at one point, I had thought it was a psychological thriller). Anyway I appreciate the writer for not mixing the two. 3 hours was long? No because you‚Äôve got two movies in one. The second one wouldn‚Äôt make sense to many without the first. The first wouldn‚Äôt be necessary without the second. The first part of the film was a documentary aiming to tell us the story everybody knows. The second part was the drama - taking us through the lives of those involved in that piece of blurry and controversial history with added sensual tensions, and it presents the story from the perspectives of both the people who were for and against the use of automic bomb; the perspectives of those who would manipulate the minds of the brilliants for their vindictiveness. Personally, I think that the goal of this film is to present people with facts and leave it to their interpretations whether one side or the other is to be held responsible for that bloody piece of history. The writer gave the audience hints throughout the film.

‚ÄúThey need us until they don‚Äôt‚Äù, words against the government.

‚ÄúI‚Äôm not sure if we can be trusted with this, but I‚Äôm sure the Nazis can‚Äôt‚Äù, Oppenheimer trying to convince himself and others they were doing it for the right cause.

‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt get to commit a sin and let others feel sorry for you‚Äù Oppenheimer‚Äôs wife after she learned the truth behind hisidday break down; which was his affair with another woman. To me, it wasn‚Äôt about the affair. It was a fore warning for what he was about to commit/achieve.

‚ÄúTry not to blow up the world‚Äù, General Groves who had always wanted to win and end the war but also showed at that moment that he cared because the bomb would destroy both the just and the unjust.

‚ÄúIt would be a terrible revelation of divine power‚Äù, Oppenheimer feeling the guilt of his creation.

"You think because you let them tar and feather you that the world will forgive you? They won't‚Äù, asked Oppenheimer‚Äôs wife.

And he said, ‚Äúwe‚Äôll see‚Äù. That was when I confirmed my thought that it was for us to travel through the story, collect all the facts and come to our own conclusion what the movie is about.

And bonus ‚Äúnow it's your turn to deal with the consequences of your achievement‚Äù said Albert Einstein.

What else makes it great?
It was the music, the acting, and the way they depict those emotions through the screen. It felt as those you were in the character‚Äôs head. You were living every bit of tension, pain, joy, pride, glory, anger, and guilt. And they kept switching those emptions, which allows you to feel those conflicting thoughts that many of the people then had. It must have been hard for them.

I went with an open mind and no expectation. And I was entertained. And please excuse my English. It‚Äôs not my first language.

author: Elaine Morrison
text: I wasn't going to watch it but I enjoyed the textbook names of the physicists showing up one by one. It was a very captivating movie, considering I was dead set against a bomb-making film. The dialogue was excellent and as has been mentioned the soundtrack underlined the tension all the way through. It travelled and didn't lag for one moment. It wasn't light entertainment, nor was it particularly deep, but highly political and I suppose a tale of when politics slip into a personal battle...and for some reason this seems to be appealing. And for some reason a movie is made about someone who attempted to poison his tutor, and for that matter I was surprised there was no sarcasm about the intentional lack of apples at Los Alamos. It seemed to be the tone of the movie to skim over and summarize a fair number of items expediently.

author: Lissa
text:
I watched this film because of the hype everywhere. Conclusion: my head is on fkng fire. I held still for almost two hours, then just slid down the chair and left without finishing it.
First of all, the film is a million hours long and it's impossible to sit through it.
Secondly, people who say that this is a masterpiece, an incredible and great story, pls explain to me: how to understand the idea of creating a nuclear bomb in "PEACE PURPOSES"? Wtf ? When there was real war in the world, people were fighting against each other, killing every day, destroying, why would it be necessary to CONSIDER creating other ways to kill millions and billions ? The film was made perfectly, with great actors, sets, effects, everything is super. The main question is: how can people admire negative things and support the idea of killing? It's great to be a scientist ,creating something new, something that hasn't been done in the world before, but how can you wake up every day with the idea in your head "I'm working on building a bomb"? The word "bomb" equals death. They're sick in the head? If you are a scientist - then create something noble, good, kind, something that will help to know the world better, that people will be able to use in the future, that will remain for other generations.

I just don't have words. If the film had shown the horror of the idea and the tragedy - I would have understood. But it showed the father of the bomb that everyone admired... sorry but that‚Äôs really minus ten out of ten. üëéüèºü§¨

author: The Great Bamboozler
text: Meh...  I'm seriously wondering how much of this film is historically accurate. I haven't gone back to do the research yet. Beyond this being three hours of super close-ups Cillian Murphy and then telling the story of the the poor socialist Ladies Man who was being hounded an oppressed by evil conservative government I didn't see that much else other than some really neat special effects. It avoids the fact that during the 1940s and 50s America had a legitimate fear of the Soviet Union and socialism because the Soviets had told us they were going to come after us. Once again the moral of this story is that the poor oppressed socialist Outcast who happens to be a very successful Ladies Man is supremely compassionate and loving toward his fellow man and the party worker all against the big bad American government it was hyperactive against socialism and communism. There it is in a nutshell. So if you want to celebrate socialism and avoid the bigger story which was the development of the bomb and the emotional fight that Truman had to go through to justify dropping it then maybe it's the movie for you

text: Do you want to understand why these two movies were presented as a package? They are showing you the new modern warfare dynamic. It's a reveal of the hand. They're showing you without telling you. They are pink bombing the future. Turning a society gay and trans is effectively a bomb to the plausible future generations that would've existed if the society wasn't introduced to the propaganda. It's the new methodology of Warfare and that is the message behind the surface of these films. You're scared of the real bomb, the explosive bomb. You revere it's destructive power as much as you fear it. Look at this! This is danger! Not this over here. This thing over here; the pink bomb, is fun and safe and silly and most importantly harmless. Right?! They are bombing the future through propaganda. The bomb is pink. Do you see it? It's a metaphor.

author: jack I wanna paint!
text:
I thought the movie sucked. I am interested in the bomb and have read lets say 20 books on the subject including The Making Of The Atomic Bomb by Richard Rhodes‚Äîa terrific book. But this movie was 60% turned over to the subject of Oppenheimer and the congressional hearings called following the war to grill him on his commie sympathies and yank his security clearance. Is anything less worth listening to‚Äîor watching‚Äîthan a congressional hearing? All this jabbering‚Äîon and on and on. ¬†¬†I was in a coma.¬†¬†What about this Robert Strauss guy? Who he‚Äîa figure lost to history. I am there¬†¬†to see a movie about The Bomb and how it was made‚Äîhands down, the profound event of the 20th century‚Äîor maybe any century‚Äî with all this fascinating science behind it beginning with Ernest Rutherford and the splitting of the atom.
This is a film for Netflix when a loser is quickly identified and you click on the back to growing link and move on something more worthy of your all too precious time.
The music. The movie sucked and the music compounded the effect. Its overwhelming and relentless‚Äîon and on and on‚Äîlike all that jabbering.¬†¬†I kept waiting for a scene with Oppenheimer in the toilet taking a leak with the violins sawing away.¬†
This is a masterpiece? Give me Barbie

author: Bang Nguyen
text: I will be the iconoclast here, but just went to see IMAX yesterday and didn't like the movie.  First of all, Robert Oppenheimer has been my scientist hero since my days as a physics/philosophy major in college.  I admire him for his intellectual prowess and his interests in Eastern and Hindu philosophies.  But this film almost completely ignored these interesting aspects of the man.  Instead, it spent so much time on the politics which to me was an uninteresting and painful part of the man's life.  Why did this film need to be filmed in IMAX format when 90% of it was just people incessantly talking to each other?

author: Tien Lee
text:
Fooled you all, eh?
The sharp cutting, overbearing thunderous sounds giving the entire movie a vaguely disturbing feel and experience designed to transfer to the viewer, in my opinion, a distaste for everyone represented in the movie connected to the bombs , coupled with total omissions of what horrors Nazis and Japanese were doing, chopping people's heads off and/or disemboweling them by the millions all over Asia and Europe. Very Nazi-esque tactics, similar gigantic sins of omission that German and Japanese high command told their countrymen and women at home, lying the whole time so their citizens kept supporting their cause...believing they were on the moral high ground when in fact they weren't, kind of scarily like what's been going on with worldwide financial elites these days...
No footage of what was going on with the Nazis and Imperial Japanese's first strike plans to make nuclear weapons which NECESSITATED everything that went on in the movie.
And lest you are also fooled by Nazi propaganda today that Japan was surrendering, a good friend of mine in Japan whose brother-in-law was formerly a rep for Japan to the United Nations literally told me that Japan was actively trying to make a bomb right up until the end.
Wake up young people in America...just because your parents and/or grandparents got divorced, it doesn't mean they were lying to you about how bad Nazis and Imperial Japanese were during WWII...those 1940s Germans and Japanese invaders bore more resemblance to Halloween and Friday the 13th killers than most 21st century Germans and Japanese of today.
Signed, A born USA citizen since the 1960s.

author: Lori Christie
text:
Felt devastated at the end of this film, the bomb was truly a miracle from Satan. This movie will leave you ashamed by our humanity.

Being born in the 2000s I've always known the reality that the world could end at a click of a button and I've always tried not to think about it too seriously because that wouldn't change that fact... But this movie makes you think about it seriously and how cruel the joke is. You're emersed in Oppenheimer's struggle between loyalty to his country and being the creator of a weapon that could end everything. I realize now that my belief that 'I don't care because I can't control it', is just a shield from the emotions I felt watching this movie and how I felt as a kid first discovering the horror and sadistic reality the bomb brings.

author: Karen Dawn Kennedy
text: Enter my director.  Take a bow,  Chris.  His resume will shock you.  He's been doing this forever,  one of the greatest storytellers of all time.  My personal favorite memento which he wrote for me way back in the day to wake me up.  And batman with Heath as the joker,  and Tenet which talked about time being malleable and in fact an illusion altogether. So when Chris sent me a signal that the flags on Oppenheimer were wrong, i thought well that makes sense cuz he had 100M to make his film and his hundreds of experts didn't catch that flag thing.  Hahaha morons. Well done Chris got should get an Oscar! Meanwhile i was on set with an incredible indie team making a pilot with 250k and when we noticed our swastikas were backwards we ground production to a halt to fix them,  but Chris's team were blind.  Oh please. The message was clear to be.  A nuclear war was imminent. So full disclosure was critical. So that happened and here we are. No Nukes it fucks with the fish! We can find better ways.  One love.

I hated how he was treated in the end, it was cruel and unfair, but I was proud that he had people fighting for him.

author: DesigninMind1
text:
This is not a documentary and as such only depicts a theatrical representation of Oppenheimer‚Äôs views at the time, through a biased reconstructive historic narrative.

Unfortunately the ultimate product; the Japanese civilian suffering is wholly missed and to not recognise this fact; truly does the film the biggest damage.

An estimated 200,000 children, women and men in that order of importance suffered to provide the only true legacy which is to serve as the start of Cold War arms race. This In turn provides the incubation period for the ‚Äúmutually assured destruction ‚Äú scenario world we live in today.

Oppenheimer being a scientist and not a political puppet should have been depicted as the great scientist he was; not the pawn he became for the military and politicians.

Wholly didn‚Äôt enjoy the film and left the cinema with the feeling that the message should have been ‚Ä¶

The ultimate price; the loss of humanity in killing innocent Japanese children .

God bless the Hibakusha

author: Dark tales from the silver screen.
text:
This film is inaccurate because Nolan puts Oppenheimer's wife at the site where the Trinity bomb test took place. She was never present. Secondly, the people of New Mexico where subjected to a radiation level 10k more than what would be a safe dose. There is no mention of the 1000's of residents situated near the bomb and the after effects of testing this bomb . Truman was a moron and the dropping of Fat Man & Little Boy showed the full destructiveness of this weapon and I pray to God the use of this bomb never sees the light of day ever again.
Putting in explicit sex scenes to show Oppenheimer was a ladies man has no bearing on the man who once said " Now I am become death , the destroyer of worlds". This film could have done so much more, but failed to tell the truth. I give this film 0 stars.

I‚Äôve seen it twice now and can‚Äôt wait to go again. A briskly paced 3 hr epic that‚Äôs essentially an action chamber piece. People in rooms planning which doesn‚Äôt sound exciting but Nolan uses pure unadulterated cinema to make it one of the most exciting movies I‚Äôve seen on the big screen in a long long time.

I‚Äôve always admired Nolan but was never a fanboy of his work and Oppenheimer changed all that. He creates such tense emotion that at times the film threatens to break under the weight of its own gravity in a good way. Couldn‚Äôt recommend it more

author: Astha Yadav
text:
This film moved me to tears, the life and story of Oppenheimer, how well it was all presented, and how it all coincided at the end.
What struck me the most was the portrayal of his feelings and thoughts after the bomb was dropped. How he looked in the audience of people applauding and laughing for at least one more person to be as horrified as him. How he let them tear his life apart by pieces as to punish himself, but in the end as Einstein said "After they have punished you enough, they will call you, award you and say all is forgiven, just remember it will all be for them, not for you."
Every. Single. Thing. About this movie was PERFECT.

Edit:
apparently it's a crime in modern world to have an opinion about something without writing 1000 words to sound politically correct; i am a filmmaker, i loved the movie as a story, and the very clear anti-nuclear message; i thought people who could write comments would have the reading comprehension to see i wrote "movie" - was oppenheimer a good or a bad person? that's what the movie tackles - HIS PERSONAL LIFE - get it?? There are a TONNE of movies on political, ethical and moral qualms of war, on the realistic effects; this is a BIOGRAPHY - now pls stfu and stop spamming my notifications

author: honeysugar1
text:
With all the hype on this movie being so amazing, i booked tickets to watch this on a Sunday morning (given it's 3 hours I want to make sure I have the rest of the day to do my chores!).

God, was this movie unnecessarily long... and boring. I love a good scientific movie but hardly got much of that and only got like 15 mins of action when they tested out the bomb towards the end of the movie. And the movie didn't even give us an opportunity to understand the scale and impact of the bomb being dropped on hiroshima and nagasaki. Disappointing really.

Watching the actual documentaries of the atomic bomb were probably MUCH more interesting than this piece of political "drama".

I want my 3 hours back! Should have gone seen Barbie

author: S. Adam Bernstein
text: Cillian Murphy did a passable job, but the film was ruined by Matt Demon and Robert Downey Jr. whose overacting was worse than I expected. Maybe he thought he was yelling at the BBC, Also I didn't expect so much devoted to the security clearance issue. As far as I'm concerned it's a footnote; this film makes it the main subject. And lots of dialogue obviously made up by the writer/director. Then there's the unnecessary switching back and forth between black and white and color; how pretentious. A Man and A Woman did it because the director couldn't afford all color; here it's the director's fake "artistic decision"; give us a break! Finally the volume was so loud I had to cover my ears. Anyway If anyone wants to see a film about the Manhattan Project there are plenty of others: the Sam Waterston one, the Paul Newman/John Cusack one, etc.

author: Buzz Buzzard
text: I have mixed feelings about this movie. It tells the story of the atom bomb which absolutely needs to be told as one of the most pivotal inventions in human history. However, after having seen HBO¬¥s Chernobyl I expected something similar and this could sadly not top Chernobyl in its mixture of drama, action and story telling, although there was plenty of potential there with nazi Germany, Japan, the end of WW2 etc. Chernobyl is the peak of exciting drama and story telling and this couldn¬¥t measure up. (Although it needs to be said that Chernobyl probably took more creative liberty for dramatic effect while Oppenheimer was frequently more understated and psychological) It¬¥s not a bad movie at all and I don¬¥t regret having seen it but it¬¥s not the greatest movie of all time either and not necessarily even Nolans best movie and it did drag out at times and 3 hours is a very long time to sit down for a movie, particularly when it fails to fully engage you.  I would recommend to see it but go into it with the mindset of watching a documentary and not an action film. Ultimately I ended up not being as excited watching this as I expected to be after watching Nolans previous works.

author: The Nightmare
text:
Just got back from this.

I thought it was just okay. To be honest I left after the trinity test for reasons I'll explain below.

The casting is great and the acting is great. Especially since there are so many big names on the screen here, they really do disappear into their roles. Robert Downey Jr. is great, Matt Damon was also great as Groves. Murphy is an excellent Oppenheimer of course and I thought it was really cool to see Benny Safdie here as well after watching Uncut Gems and Good Time.

The big issue with this movie is that it skips around between three time periods throughout the film. The cuts back and forth tire you out quickly as you try to keep track of several story lines at once. The big problem this creates is that you never really get into a flow state with the movie. They constantly break the narrative going back and forth and so all of a sudden they're doing the trinity test and you wonder how you wound up there. You're at the big climactic moment of the film but it doesn't really feel like you've built up to it. It just kind of happens... Because that's how the movie goes, it's like a disorganized deck of photos from mixed time periods that were put back together in the wrong order. The consequence of this is that everything just feels shallow. You're just seeing these snapshots in time, but you're skipping over the surface of them. The film is three hours long but you never really feel like you engage with anything that's going on.

I've seen other reviews that have alluded to the same things - they said they didn't really know why... but they just felt bored. The film didn't deliver the emotional punch they thought it would. I'd give it a 7/10 because I think there are some really great things in here, they're just not arranged in a way that works well.

EDIT: Forgot to add - the reason I left after the trinity test was that I was not able to hear a lot of the dialogue. I had missed so many names and plot points by then that I knew the big event was over and it was likely just the political hearings afterwards. Since I was already lost on that front I just decided to leave. I'll watch it with subtitles when it comes out on streaming and see if I like it a second time. It seems like Christopher Nolan films get a bad rep for having poor audio mixing, not sure if anyone else noticed this? Softer spoken lines were hard to hear.

author: DOOM Studios
text:
Christopher Nolan‚Äôs ‚ÄúOppenheimer‚Äù is an absolute beast of a film, It is so well made I can not recommend it enough. For anyone who expected it to be a film on the trinity bomb only it would be a bad film, but it was a movie on the life of J. Robert Oppenheimer, which I think Nolan grasped pretty well with the little cuts of the ups and downs of his life, It could be considered boring if your attention span is 10 seconds, but for anyone who has even a slight interest in the conversations, the movie is phenomenal, even the part after the bomb where it was just dialogues upon dialogues of security clearance, the movie held its ground well, like i said the movie was about the life of J. Robert Oppenheimer, and going through that final hour of the film. We were made to feel exactly like he felt, anxious, frustrated and saddened on each betrayal by characters we had bonded with over time and likewise each triumph.
It is one of the best movies I‚Äôve seen this year to understand it more clearly i would recommend you watch Veritasium's video on ‚ÄúWhy Does Oppenheimer Deserves His Own Movie.‚Äù since it broadly encompasses the whole movie and it allows you to follow along very well.

I absolutely recommend it.

author: Aba Zaba
text:
Oppenheimer is essentially a biographical story told in un chronological order (but in order) which effectively is the story of a group of about 170 people responsible for building the first atomic bomb and the part is played well by Cillian Murphy. However, there is an element of the character that is missing in the story. He is supposed to be a forlorn guilt-ridden man who is walked over and his guilt is the effective thing that plagues him.

He is supposed to have an edge of harshness and edge of rebellion and simultaneously overwhelming edge of guilt the translates into him being able to be taken advantage of and, not being able to ever see past himself. I believe that edge of guilt...that most important element of this, in this documentary quote, you can see the self loathing hate.

That is the most important way inside of that transition in the character but there's an element of the character missing which is the self loathing guilt-to-hate which would lead the character to implode and be self obsessed, which I think that self contempt is just missing.

Obviously, it is still very relevant to his obsession with it existing in the first place.

Cillian Murphy plays the character very well. This implosion, of the character, which effectively has the character have blinders on when there are moments that are too traumatic and this is sometimes missing in the character, I feel the story could have stuck a little better. It is an element of the character that has him hide away from existence... moments that are too difficult and shut things off from his consciousness that otherwise he would remember and this is of course the crux of the character, are partly missing in the character.

So even though he did a great job and I think he's a fantastic actor and obviously his career is well ahead of him and I think he should get an Oscar nomination. This is his first big role so kudos to him for the performance and that's just one thing that I noticed that I felt was missing.

Christopher Nolan does a beautiful job putting everything you can into a 3-hour film. I wish that it would have been about 10 minutes shorter. (Could we have seen a countdown sequence against Nazis) I also feel like it's interesting since he got robbed from nomination for the dark night. He's been jamming the films that he's been making since that point in time in his career putting everything he can into as many seconds.
People are scared of film length and a version in order would be cool. However, I do appreciate and respect that he's able to cram everything into his films as well.
That ten minutes could savor stronger moments that were shorter.
I liked his artistic choice to make the bomb a silent moment.
Given the tension in the film it was either that or, like Interstellar, mix silence with ear bleeding sound. I might like to see that.
A few music choices drowned out dialogue
(I would have liked to see the bomb scene with the ear bleeding sound)

The performances I think to Nolan, Cillian will get nominated as well I think Downey Jr. might, as well as Blunt and Damon.

The Documentary clip. I am become death destroyer of worlds, there is a missing element was just the fact that it comes from a Hindu text which describes thousands of years ago an atomic bomb going off which Oppenheimer was quite obsessed with though that could probably never be in such a story.

Grade: A-

author: Himalayan Tiger
text:
The Bhagvad Gita wasn't translated to English by Bob, but by his tutor at UC Berkeley, Arthur Ryder. The original Sanskrit version says "Kaal". Kaal means Time.

Context: In the battle of Mahabharata, on the battlefield, the prince Arjuna felt helpless on seeing his loved ones on the other side of the battlefield. He knew his battle skills & thought that while fighting his own cousins & teachers, he'd end up killing them or at least severely injuring them. This threw him into a dilemma (much like what Oppenheimer faced after the nuclear tests). His charioteer, Krishna, tried to motivate him, but in vain. In a sort of last ditch attempt, Krishna who is actually the avatar of Lord Vishnu, took the form of his Eternal Self, as Lord Vishnu, and recited the Gita to Arjuna, telling him how he needs to do his duties because He i.e. God, intended it that way. Lord Vishnu's detailed advice is what the Bhagvad Gita basically is.

This dialogue that has now become world famous, appears in Chapter 11, verse 32. In it, Vishnu says he's 'Kaal', or Time... contextually meaning, the Time-Spirit. What he meant to tell Arjuna was He is Time, and Time comes for all. Time is actually the ultimate destroyer. Think about it .. every second we waste, is a second destroyed & never coming back. What Vishnu meant to convey to Arjuna was, whether you do your duties or no, Time finally comes for us all, so keep doing your duties to the best of your abilities & let Time take care of everything else.

This 'Kaal' was wrongly translated by Oppenheimer's tutor Ryder, as 'Death'.

It should actually mean, "I am the Time-Spirit, the destroyer of worlds."

author: Nothing\
text:
Once I realized there's a love story shoehorned into this movie, which has no place for a love story, I'm no longer excited to see the movie. Then when I heard there's a scene where he recites the Bagada Vita line "Now I am become death, destroyer of worlds" while screwing some broad, instead of while reflecting on the implications of what he's done with the bomb like what happened in real life. I'm just downright disappointed. Christopher Nolan did this same crap with Interstellar. It was supposed to be based on science, except for the fact that they say love is the only force that transcends time and space and that Cooper was being guided by his love for his daughter entire time.

After seeing one potentially good movie after another being turned into crap by a shoehorned love story for the better part of 30 years, I have no interest in seeing any more. So, I'm not even going to bother with this movie. But I will watch Barbie. Not even kidding. I'd rather see Barbie than a movie about the Manhattan project with a fuckin' love story in it.

author: Michael Williams
text:
Just come back from seeing this in IMAX with my dad and a few others. This film is truly remarkable, however, for those who haven't seen I have to warn you of one or two things:
Firstly, the dialogue clarity in this film was terrible. I say that bitterly because this has the potential to be one of the most powerful films. I explained to my mum with my dad about it and I literally understood about 20% of the dialogue. Hollywood seriously needs to get to grips with actors and their dialogue clarity. Music and sound effects are sky rocketing, but dialogue is going down. Bear in mind, I saw this in Imax where the sound knocks you off your feet, and much to my horror I could barely understand it. Even when certain characters shouted it was hard work and I'm 24 years of age! If anyone understood had a different experience I'm happy for you.
With regards to nude scenes (I know there's been a bit of controversy over it) they were rather explicit, but they made sense from a film making point of view. The film is largely about what happens when we make the wrong choices and the effect those choices and actions have. The nude scenes conveyed the sort of inner confusion and discomfort that was within him. So I both agree and disagree with them.
Apart from that, powerful film! The ending scene was one of the greatest cinematic experiences I've ever had, truly truly powerful.
Also a fun fact about some of the music that I was getting was that it sounded like sirens.

author: wednesday adams
text:
Watch ‚ÄúAtomic Homefront‚Äù.

Nuclear waste from the Manhattan Project was illegally dumped underground in a landfill. For the last several years an uncontrolled, subsurface fire has been moving towards an area where the radioactive waste was buried. In August 2016, the EPA admitted that *the radioactive waste was less than 700 feet from the fire*.

This is right next to two residential areas where the residents all live, unable to leave, all of their homes are contaminated with high levels of radiation. They have to be prepared to flee at any moment because no one knows when the fire will meet the radioactive waste. So many of the residents have cancer and health problems caused by living in a contaminated hellhole, with no relocation offers or real solution.

author: MrsRJ Lupin
text:
https://youtu.be/Qk_zpjK3cTo

America wouldn't have had the Manhattan project had it not been for George Paget Thomson, Chadwick and the collaboration of the British theoreticians and experimentalists Cockcroft, Peiers, Oliphant, Tuck, Thomson and more, many more. Chadwick, neutron discoverer and Nobel winner had his own section at Los Alamos, and he and Groves got on very well, in fact it was Chadwick (who had known Bohr from pre WW1 days in Manchester under Rutherford) had been the one instrumental in getting Bohr out of Sweden to Scotland and then out to Los Alamos. I can only think Nolan literally based the film on the book he read and did no other research as to why these scientists weren't even name checked, on the principle that one should never assign to malice what could equally be attributed to incomptence. But, if you are clear that Nolan isn't incompetent, however...

author: Arya
text: HBO's Chernobyl did a far superior job in portraying a similar subject matter with actual human stakes and relatable characters. It's not because of the longer runtime, Nolan just has a totally different approach. An antagonist like Strauss seems so meaningless to me in the greater context of what Oppenheimer means to the world. A real antagonist would have been someone who challenged Oppenheimer's determination to build a bomb to begin with, not someone like Strauss who thought more about his career and personal insults by Oppenheimer. Or it could have been Trueman, an antagonist later in Oppenheimer's life when he finished the bomb, but wouldn't want it to be used. Neither Trueman nor bomb critics got any real screentime.

author: Baji
text:
Julius Robert Oppenheimer was a physicist and director of the Los Alamos laboratory during the development of the atomic bomb after the Nazi and Soviet invasion of Poland in 1939. He was selected to administrate the repertory carrying out the Manhattan project. This program developed the first generations of atomic weapons, with the first weapons being used at the end of the Second World War from 1939 to 1945. After his resignation in 1945 from the Manhattan project due to the destructive power of Little Man and Fat Boy, he became the chairman and general adviser to the committee of the Atomic Energy Commission also before the murder and assassination of Pres John F. Kennedy in 1963 Kennedy announced that Oppenheimer would be receiving Enrico Fermi award for his extraordinary achievement in physics. He was presented this reward by Lyndon B Johnson, president, after Kennedy‚Äôs assassination on December 1963.

Julius Robert but I‚Äôm was born in the city of New York to German and Jewish immigrants on April 22, 1904; after he graduated from the University of Harvard, he went to the English university of Cambridge, where he began his research into topics at the Cavendish Laboratory in 1925. During his time at Gottingen, he teamed up with Max Born; Niels Bohr received a doctorate at Gottingen while also developing what became known as the Born-Oppenheimer method, which was a contribution to quantum molecular theory. Oppenheimer died on 18th February 1967 of throat cancer.

Julius Robert Oppenheimer became politically active in the 1930s and agreed with Leo Szilard and Albert Einstein that Nazi Germany could potentially develop their own atomic weapons. With the invasion of Poland in 1939 by Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union, the Manhattan project was started for the United States to harness the potential of atomic weapons before their rivals of the Japanese Empire or the Third Reich/Nazi Germany built their own. Oppenheimer led the project from Los Alamos in New Mexico beginning in 1942. The project itself was full of scientists that fled Nazi Germany. Oppenheimer himself was descended from Jewish and German immigrants, making the matter of developing the first atomic weapon exceedingly personal with the bomb initially planned to attack Germany. Still, by 1944, it was apparent that the war in Europe was won, so the United States changed its plans to drop the atom bombs on the Japanese Empire due to the Empire being entrenched in the Japanese home islands and with the Japanese army successfully taking control and winning the war in China by 1945 if the bomb was not launched then the war could have continued easily until the late 1940s. The Manhattan project was initially given the funding of US $6000, with the budget accumulating to $2 billion by 1945.

author: Scott
text:
My two cents: DO. NOT. GO. TO. THIS. MOVIE. Nolan has made stylistic and editorial choices that prevent this movie from being engaging in the slightest. You will not care about the characters. You will not feel ANYTHING for them. You will not care about their motivations. Unless you already know the history, you will not know what is going on. You will be frustrated by the CEASELESS cutting away from scenes where little or nothing has even happened yet. You will be confused, then annoyed, then tortured by the score / soundscape which completely abandons the most basic tenet of performance art ‚Äî the buildup and release of tension. You will roll your eyes at the absurd use of psychedelic visual elements that add ZERO to your overall understanding / experience.

Save your money, and do something better with your time. Youtube has plenty of videos that will tell you the story of the creation of the bomb and Oppenheimer's persecution, and deliver the message of "nuke bombs bad" as effectively, or maybe even more effectively, than this film.

Edit: Minutes after posting this, I got this sneaky suspicion that I wasn't harsh enough. So to be perfectly clear: If I had not gone with two of my friends, if I had instead gone by myslef, I absolutely would have gotten up at about the 45 minute point and walked out of this turd. I stayed and suffered for the entire three hours of throbbing bullshit because I didn't want my friends to feel obligated to leave with me.

author: Whispergirl
text:
My dad is 95. He is an atomic vet. That means he was a similarly-recruited scientist (in the post Oppenheimer days) who studied the above-ground tests. The first time he told us kids about what it was like to really witness the bomb, I was in early high school, many, many years ago. He said, as a conclusion, if every leader would see it, they would destroy them all. He is a man of few words, but his words about what it was like to witness his team's test bombs are unforgettable. Today, he just had heart surgery. This week, after recovery, my brother plans to take him to see this movie. The only opinion I care about concerning this movie is his. I wonder how similar that discussion about this movie will be to the first discussion I had with him when he talked about the experience of his own. I haven't seen the movie yet, but I am hopeful my dad says they did it justice. Now, my decision, wait until I hear what my dad says, or go see it first?
Edit: Dad and my brother are going on August 16 to see the movie in 70mmIMAX. I saw it last Friday. I'll update after August 16, and at some point, video our dad. Thank you so much for this outpouring of support. I never anticipated it. Really, thank you.

author: Soumyadipta Majumder
text:
Oppenheimer faced many challenges in his new role. He had to recruit and manage hundreds of scientists from different disciplines and backgrounds, who often had conflicting opinions and egos.

He had to deal with the technical difficulties and dangers of working with radioactive materials and explosives. He had to cope with the pressure and secrecy of a wartime project that could determine the fate of millions of lives.

But he also had a vision. He wanted to create a bomb that would work on the principle of implosion, where a sphere of plutonium would be compressed by a surrounding shell of conventional explosives, triggering a nuclear chain reaction. He believed that this method would be more efficient and reliable than the alternative gun-type design, where two pieces of uranium would be shot together to form a critical mass.

Oppenheimer assembled a team of experts to work on the implosion concept at Los Alamos, New Mexico, where he established a remote laboratory in 1943. He also collaborated with other scientists at different sites across the country, such as Enrico Fermi at Chicago, Ernest Lawrence at Berkeley, and Hans Bethe at Cornell. He coordinated their efforts and synthesized their ideas into a coherent plan.

He also faced some opposition and skepticism from his peers and superiors. Some doubted that the implosion method would work at all, or that it would be ready in time for the war. Some questioned his loyalty and security clearance, due to his past associations with communists and pacifists. Some resented his authority and influence over the project.

But Oppenheimer persevered and prevailed. He proved himself to be a capable leader and a creative thinker, who could inspire and motivate others with his eloquence and enthusiasm. He solved many technical problems and overcame many obstacles along the way. He also developed a strong sense of responsibility and morality for his work, which he expressed in poetic and philosophical terms.

He finally achieved his goal on July 16, 1945, when he witnessed the first successful test of an atomic bomb at Trinity Site in New Mexico.

He later recalled that he was reminded of a verse from the Hindu scripture Bhagavad Gita: "Now I am become Death, the destroyer of worlds." He realized that he had unleashed a new force of nature that could change history forever.

A few weeks later, two atomic bombs based on Oppenheimer's design were dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki in Japan, killing hundreds of thousands of people and ending World War II. Oppenheimer was hailed as a hero by some and vilified as a villain by others.

He himself was ambivalent about his role in creating such a destructive weapon. He later said: "In some sort of crude sense which no vulgarity, no humor, no overstatement can quite extinguish, the physicists have known sin; and this is a knowledge which they cannot lose."

After the war, Oppenheimer became an advocate for international control of nuclear power and disarmament. He opposed the development of the hydrogen bomb, which was even more powerful than the atomic bomb. He also clashed with some political and military factions who wanted to use nuclear weapons as instruments of intimidation and domination. As a result, he was accused of being disloyal and untrustworthy by a government committee in 1954, which revoked his security clearance and stripped him of his influence.

Oppenheimer spent the rest of his life as a professor at Princeton University's Institute for Advanced Study, where he continued to teach and research on physics. He also wrote and lectured on various topics related to science, culture, philosophy, and ethics. He received several honors and awards for his contributions to science and humanity, including the Enrico Fermi Award in 1963 from President John F. Kennedy.

He died in 1967 from throat cancer at age 62. He left behind a legacy that is both admired and controversial, both celebrated and criticized. He was one of the most influential figures in modern history who shaped our understanding of nature's secrets and our ability to harness them for good or evil. He was Robert Oppenheimer: The father of the atomic bomb.

author: Soumyadipta Majumder
text: There are several books about J. Robert Oppenheimer that are considered to be excellent. One of the most well-known and highly respected is "American Prometheus: The Triumph and Tragedy of J. Robert Oppenheimer" by Kai Bird and Martin J. Sherwin. This biography covers Oppenheimer's life in great detail, including his work on the Manhattan Project and his later years as a controversial figure in the world of science and politics. Another highly recommended book is "Oppenheimer: The Tragic Intellect" by Charles Thorpe. This book provides a psychological and philosophical examination of Oppenheimer's life and work.

author: Soumyadipta Majumder
text:
Not long after the fall of Norway in 1940, British intelligence learned that the Nazis had begun accelerating their diabolical atomic weapons program. The Norwegian hydroelectric plant at Vemork, which was the world's largest heavy water mass-production site, was an essential element for the Germans to progress with their nuclear weapons programme.

The British launched 3 commando operations to disrupt the production of heavy water;

Operation Grouse - 4 Norwegians were trained to a ludicrously high level by the British in Scotland, once the 4 Commandos were ready they were dropped into the wilderness of Norway, where they survived by being total Bear Grylls level badasses. They carried out reconnaissance and gathered vital information, and prepared for the British to send a substantial commando raid.

Operation Freshman - 34 British commandos were sent to destroy the heavy water plant when it became apparent that the Germans were close to developing a nuclear reactor. The elite 34 man team was to fly in on gliders and link up with the Norwegians, to hit the Germans hard and destroy the heavy water plant.

The entire operation was a tragic disaster, a storm caused chaos, one glider and its tow plane crashed into a mountain with all commandos and pilots lost and the other glider crashed with injuries. All the survivors were eventually found by the Germans and executed on Hitler's commando order.

Operation Gunnerside - February 1943, after the previously failed operation, the British remained relentless in the mission to knock out the Nazi nuclear weapons project. Six Norwegians were trained to specialist commando level and then parachuted in to link up with the original Grouse team, which was still surviving like badasses.

The 9 men skied to the heavy water plant, then descended into a deep ravine, forded the treacherous icy river and then climbed a cliff face. Before sneaking past the substantial German guard force, and into the hydro plant.

Once inside they set about planting shed loads of explosives on the critical heavy-water electrolysis chambers. The bombs detonated and the entire inventory of heavy water produced during the German occupation was destroyed, along with the machinery to produce more. The Norwegian Commandos all escaped, skiing 300 odd kilometres to safety in Sweden.

The Norwegian squad commander told his team ahead of the mission;

‚ÄúI cannot tell you why this mission is so important, but if you succeed, it will live in Norway‚Äôs memory for a hundred years.‚Äù ‚Äî Norwegian Royal Army Colonel Leif Tronstad.

After the stunningly successful raid, it turned out the fiendish Germans had a stockpile of heavy water ready to transport in a depo near the hydro plant, the Germans loaded it onto a ferry and were set to send it across a vast lake, on its journey to Germany, where it would have been enough to carry out Hitler's nuclear program.

Only another 3 Norwegians were like ‚Äòfrack that‚Äô and they snuck onto the ferry, planting a massive explosive charge. The ferry with its valuable cargo was sunk, sending Hitler's dream of nuclear weapons to the bottom of a lake.

author: Soumyadipta Majumder
text:
‚ÄúHow close were the Nazis to developing an atomic bomb? The truth is that National Socialist Germany could not possibly have built a weapon like the atomic bombs dropped on Hiroshima or Nagasaki. This was not because the country lacked the scientists, resources, or will, but rather because its leaders did not really try.‚Äù

‚ÄúThey were certainly trying to win the war. And they were willing to devote huge amounts of resources to building rockets, jet planes, and other forms of deadly and sometimes exotic forms of military technology. So why not the atomic bomb? Nazi Germany, it turns out, made other choices and simply ran out of time.‚Äù

‚ÄúIn January of 1939, the German chemists Otto Hahn and Fritz Strassmann published the results of an historic experiment: after bombarding uranium with neutrons‚Äîneutrally charged particles‚Äîthey found barium, an element roughly half the size of uranium. Their former colleague Lise Meitner, who a few months before had been forced to flee Germany and seek refuge in Sweden, and her nephew Otto Frisch realized that the uranium nucleus had split in two. These revelations touched off a frenzy of scientific work on fission around the world.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe German "uranium project" began in earnest shortly after Germany's invasion of Poland in September 1939, when German Army Ordnance established a research program led by the Army physicist Kurt Diebner to investigate the military applications of fission. By the end of the year the physicist Werner Heisenberg had calculated that nuclear fission chain reactions might be possible. When slowed down and controlled in a "uranium machine" (nuclear reactor), these chain reactions could generate energy; when uncontrolled, they would be a "nuclear explosive" many times more powerful than conventional explosives.‚Äù

During the last months of the war, a small group of scientists working in secret built and tested a nuclear device.

‚ÄúWhereas scientists could only use natural uranium in a uranium machine, Heisenberg noted that they could use pure uranium 235, a rare isotope, as an explosive. In the summer of 1940, Carl Friedrich von Weizs√≠cker, a younger colleague and friend of Heisenberg's, drew upon publications by scholars working in Britain, Denmark, France, and the United States to conclude that if a uranium machine could sustain a chain reaction, then some of the more common uranium 238 would be transmuted into "element 94," now called plutonium. Like uranium 235, element 94 would be an incredibly powerful explosive. In 1941, von Weizs√≠cker went so far as to submit a patent application for using a uranium machine to manufacture this new radioactive element.‚Äù

‚ÄúResearchers knew that they could manufacture significant amounts of uranium 235 only by means of isotope separation. At first German scientists led by the physical chemist Paul Harteck tried thermal diffusion in a separation column. In this process, a liquid compound rises as it heats, falls as it cools, and tends to separate into its lighter and heavier components as it cycles around the column. But by 1941 they gave up on this method and started building centrifuges. These devices use centripetal force to accumulate the heavier isotopes on the outside of the tube, where they can be separated out. Although the war hampered their work, by the fall of the Third Reich in 1945 they had achieved a significant enrichment in small samples of uranium. Not enough for an atomic bomb, but uranium 235 enrichment nonetheless.‚Äù

‚ÄúUranium machines needed a moderator, a substance that would slow down the neutrons liberated by chain reactions. In the end, the project decided to use heavy water‚Äîoxygen combined with the rare heavy isotope of hydrogen‚Äîinstead of water or graphite. This was not (as one of the many myths associated with the German nuclear weapons effort had it) because of a mistake the physicist Walther Bothe made when he measured the neutron absorption of graphite. Rather, it appeared that the Norsk Hydro plant in occupied Norway could provide the amounts of heavy water they needed in the first stage of development at a relatively low cost.‚Äù

‚ÄúThe Norwegian resistance and Allied bombers eventually put a stop to Norwegian production of heavy water (see Norwegian Resistance Coup and See the Spy Messages. But by that time it was not possible to begin the production of either pure graphite or pure heavy water in Germany. In the end, the German scientists had only enough heavy water to conduct one or two large-scale nuclear reactor experiments at a time.‚Äù

Heisenberg and his colleagues did not push as hard as they could have to make atomic bombs.

‚ÄúBy the very end of the war, the Germans had progressed from horizontal and spherical layer designs to three-dimensional lattices of uranium cubes immersed in heavy water. They had also developed a nuclear reactor design that almost, but not quite, achieved a controlled and sustained nuclear fission chain reaction. During the last months of the war, a small group of scientists working in secret under Diebner and with the strong support of the physicist Walther Gerlach, who was by that time head of the uranium project, built and tested a nuclear device.‚Äù

‚ÄúAt best this would have been far less destructive than the atomic bombs dropped on Japan. Rather it is an example of scientists trying to make any sort of weapon they could in order to help stave off defeat. No one knows the exact form of the device tested. But apparently the German scientists had designed it to use chemical high explosives configured in a hollow shell in order to provoke both nuclear fission and nuclear fusion reactions. It is not clear whether this test generated nuclear reactions, but it does appear as if this is what the scientists had intended to occur.‚Äù

‚ÄúAll of this begs the question, why did they not get further? Why did they not beat the Americans in the race for atomic bombs? The short answer is that whereas the Americans tried to create atomic bombs, and succeeded, the Germans did not succeed, but also did not really try.‚Äù

‚ÄúThis can best be explained by focusing on the winter of 1941-1942. From the start of the war until the late fall of 1941, the German "lightning war" had marched from one victory to another, subjugating most of Europe. During this period, the Germans needed no wonder weapons. After the Soviet counterattack, Pearl Harbor, and the German declaration of war against the United States, the war had become one of attrition. For the first time, German Army Ordnance asked its scientists when it could expect nuclear weapons. The German scientists were cautious: while it was clear that they could build atomic bombs in principle, they would require a great deal of resources to do so and could not realize such weapons any time soon.‚Äù

‚ÄúArmy Ordnance came to the reasonable conclusion that the uranium work was important enough to continue at the laboratory scale, but that a massive shift to the industrial scale, something required in any serious attempt to build an atomic bomb, would not be done. This contrasts with the commitment the German leadership made throughout the war to the effort to build a rocket. They sunk enormous resources into this project, indeed, on the scale of what the Americans invested in the Manhattan Project.‚Äù

‚ÄúThus Heisenberg and his colleagues did not slow down or divert their research; they did not resist Hitler by denying him nuclear weapons. With the exception of the scientists working on Diebner's nuclear device, however, they also clearly did not push as hard as they could have to make atomic bombs. They were neither heroes nor villains, just scientists working on weapons of mass destruction for Hitler's Germany.‚Äù

author: RAGHUVEER MADUVINAKODY
text:
Movie making may have been good. But, it is disgusting to know that Oppenheimer quoted the Hindu holy book to be his inspiration. It gives totally a distorted view of Hinduism to the world, whereas, Hinduism preaches that the world is one family (Vasudaiva Kutumbakam).

Oppenheimer did not deserve to quote Bhagavad-Gita, with his half baked understanding of the content and Hinduism for two reasons.
1. In Hinduism there are three categories of knowledge or understanding. They are 'Agyan' meaning ignorance, 'Sugyan' meaning right knowledge and 'Viparith Gyan' meaning perverted understanding. So, Hinduism preaches that, for the right understanding, a Guru or teacher is a must. Bhagavad-Gita is a treatise that gives a different understanding with every reading. Three universal teachers of Hinduism ie., Shankaracharya, Ramanujacharya and Madhwacharya have given different interpretations of the holy book. Such is the deep meaning of the content of the book. Someone can't just pick a copy of it, read and claim to have understood it. Oppenheimer just did this. He didn't even have a spiritual Guru. He didn't ever pray God or practice any faith in his life. This says it all about him.
2. He claims himself to be the destroyer of the world, by quoting Bhagavad-Gita. Is this belief not found in Christianity? What about the belief of ' Day of last judgement' then? Did he not read Bible?

No matter what Oppenheimer had meant, his quoting of a verse from Bhagavad-Gita in the context of his heinous act and propagating it sends wrong perception of Hinduism to the world and deeply hurts the sentiments of Hindus, who are essentially tolerant and peace-loving community.
Om shanthi. Amen.

author: Follower of Jakob Lorber
text: Great movie but nuclear power was invented earlier. Long time ago there was another planet in our solar system between Mars and Jupiter on which (giant) humans lived. They too invented nuclear power, but in a war they misused that nuclear power and the planet was destroyed. Only the four moons of that planet survived the destruction. The asteroid belt between Mars and Jupiter is the visible remaining part of that destruction. The name of that planet was Mallona, Mallona means 'broken planet'. To the old Greeks Mallona was known as Phaeton. In the books of Jakob Lorber and Leopold Engel you can find more information about that.

author: Avishek Biswas
text:
Mediocre movie for me.. just because it is Nolan directed doesnt mandate it to be a good movie..

Main issue was - there was no coherence in the movie.. throughout the 180min it felt like Mr Nolan just glued together some scenes.. background music seemed unnecessary at certain points ..

More focus on showing politics in the movie as opposed to showing more around scientific stuffs - which is why i feel the thumbnail on the trailer is misdirecting audience.. the thumbnail gives a vibe that the movie will be about some hifi scientific stuffs whereas it was more about the politics around Trinity and Manhattan project..

And finally i am a fan of non-linear movies but only when it is done properly.. Nolan did a very poor job of the non-linearity in this movie.. too many abrupt scene switch and that happened for 3 hours..

I would rate is max 6 out of 10‚Ä¶

author: RUSTY SUNSHINE
text:
It doesn't matter how many movies Chris makes; Memento will be my favorite of his works because it had no pomp and circumstance, no effects, and was as clean a script and cinema experience as they come. I thought he was going to be David Lynch, but he didn't go in that direction. He has my respect for making big movies, but Memento is something to always go back to. Saw it in LA the day it came out and instantly knew there was a director there. It's the forever reminder that in his old age, when he gets there and if he gets there, and he's tired, something small like Memento might be the way to finish it all off with the cherry on top. I don't need a big movie to know when I see a GREAT movie. Memento remains in my top 500 of the best movies ever made. None of his other movies are on that list of 500 for me, and I've seen 10,000 movies.

For perspective? He still hasn't hit Kurosawa, and too much music is the problem. But, I'm not sure you can EVER take that great of a risk with 200+ million dollar budgets. Seven Samurai; a masterpiece, made $170,000,000 adjusted for inflation, and that movie is in my top 50. It's unbelievable and makes modern filmmakers shudder when they think they've made something worth a damn. Chris is trying to make movies in a comic book world. I understand the business. It shifts filmmakers.

I don't know how I even feel by saying "I hope this does well at the box office" and let's say I didn't say that because, well, some of us never wanted to see anything but the History Channel to even cope. Perhaps I'm just getting older, and I should come to terms with this new generation needing to see it. Maybe that's the point. F*ck the box office because these kids need to know.

Spielberg handled his piece of the Holocaust. Nolan did the atomic bomb. Spielberg dealt with pure evil men. Nolan is dealing with evil, indifference, apathy and running out of time while making an object that is evil to stop evil and the decisions to drop it on the Japanese (twice) doesn't hold up in light of humanity. They made fire. They made a giant and horrific ball of fire. There were once little Japanese boys and girls in their rooms, and then; there weren't. I can't reconcile that.

Maybe the only thing I really wrote here worth a damn was my properly placed semicolon in the prior paragraph which is the literary expression of the gasping breath taken after the concept of children gone with the pause brought on by a single punctuation few will notice in a donut flavored modern world.

Thanks for making it? Do you mean the bomb or the movie? Anyway, the closest thing we have to a new modern problem at the scale of the development of the nuclear bomb is the development of Donald J. Trump and trying to stop Hitler all over again. But, in this case, perhaps slightly less than half of America is fine with us dropping a bomb on ourselves with a single, maddening, quite insane reelection. Americans seem to like playing with fire, or atleast seeing what it can possibly do.

Oppenheimer had an ordered task he could have abandoned. Trump has a task we must all put a stop to. After all, in November 2024, we may very well have a red button to push to stop him while others push a red button to make him so. At that point, some of us are just trying to cut the circuit to the launch of a madman in a numbers game.

Watched it today and it is a typical Christopher Nolan masterpiece.

You need some level of intelligence to understand what‚Äôs going on because even when dumbed down to the bare basics, it‚Äôs still a lot to take in. I‚Äôm not talking about the physics, which has wisely been left to a small portion of the film. But the morality of it all.

If you are a peace loving hippy, you will hate this film. If you are a Gung-ho ‚Äònuke em all‚Äô person, you will hate this film. The film does not debate the existence of nuclear weapons, or the encouragement for bigger and better. But merely the limitation and control of nuclear weapons.

And lastly spoiler alert, the bomb goes boom

author: Mike Morrissey
text:
I saw it last night and it was long, slow, boring, and over-rated. I appreciate sophisticated movie plots but this is not for your average viewer as it will put you to sleep in the first hour (which it drags on for three btw).

It's not just about the atom bomb, it's about Oppenheimer's connection with the Communist party, investigations, hearings, and how he lost his security clearance. I understood the complexity of the movie I just didn't find it interesting. You need to have a very deep understanding of who he was and what happened back in the day and if you don't then you're going to need to a shot of espresso to stay awake.

The acting was great, Oppenheimer was a remarkable person, but I don't jump on the critic's bandwagon who rave about something as such. It's deep with lots of layers sure, but you still have to make it palatable and interesting to watch. Nolan is definitely talented but therein lies where he lacks greatly.

author: Md Anas

THAT. That feeling is astonishing.

And mind you everyone reading this, even though you've watched the trailer (it's now after watching the movie that I'm watching it), you certainly shouldn't miss out on this masterpiece. Unless you have a home theatre, for which you'll still have to wait and avoid spoilers, concluding, GO Watch the film.

And for once try to follow my way of watching blockbusters. Every second and every dime will feel worth it.

author: Rebecca Turner
text: Oppenheimer and his acolytes may not have known then all that their terrifying creation wreaked, but we do today, including the fact that, according to journalist John Hershey‚Äôs 1946 nonfiction account, Hiroshima, shadows were literally blasted from presumably incinerated human beings and imprinted on walls, like ghostly murals. Unfortunately, Nolan pulls his punches and cops out by never explicitly showing what the bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki cost in human terms. Unlike the Trinity test in the empty desert, the horrifying explosions in Japan are alluded to but never depicted per se in this movie.

author: Ron Ruggieri
text:
FACTS about J. Robert Oppenheimer :
[ "After the war, Oppenheimer chaired the U.S. Atomic Energy Commission. He opposed developing an even more powerful hydrogen bomb. When President Truman finally approved it, Oppenheimer did not argue, but his initial reluctance and the political climate turned against him. In 1953, at the height of U.S. anticommunist feeling, Oppenheimer was accused of having communist sympathies, and his security clearance was taken away. He had, in fact, had friends who were communists, mostly people involved in the antifascist movement of the thirties. This loss of security clearance ended Oppenheimer's influence on science policy. He held the academic post of director of the Institute of Advanced Study at Princeton, and in the last years of his life, he thought and wrote much about the problems of intellectual ethics and morality. He died of throat cancer in 1967. "]
