author: vibhvesh chandel
text:
In a world where the power to annihilate lies within humanity's grasp, the atomic bomb serves as a grim reminder of the destructive potential we hold. Across nations, the possession of these weapons has triggered an alarming arms race, raising concerns about the future of global security.

As we bear witness to rising tensions and the development of more powerful weapons, it becomes imperative to unite as a global community, advocating for peace and working towards a world free from the menace of nuclear warfare.

The recent events in Russia and Ukraine serve as stark reminders of the devastating consequences of armed conflicts and territorial disputes. The war-torn region faces untold human suffering, loss of innocent lives, and vast destruction of infrastructure. These tragic events underscore the urgent need for peaceful resolutions and diplomatic dialogue.

In the face of adversity, let us stand united in calling for an end to hostilities and a return to the negotiating table. We must prioritize global cooperation, understanding, and empathy over violence and hatred. By fostering a culture of dialogue and reconciliation, we can pave the way for lasting peace and mutual respect.

It is time for us to reflect on the lessons of history and make a collective commitment to being advocates of peace. We must be instruments of change, encouraging our leaders to prioritize diplomacy and peaceful means to resolve conflicts.

As we aspire towards a world where nuclear weapons are but a distant memory, we must remember that the path to peace is not a solitary journey. It requires collective efforts and unwavering determination to safeguard the future of our planet and all its inhabitants.

Let us raise our voices together, embracing the vision of a peaceful world, where wars are replaced with cooperation, understanding, and compassion. The road to peace may be arduous, but with perseverance and unity, we can forge a brighter future, free from the shadow of the atomic bomb.

In solidarity for peace and humanity,

text:
As i see the trailer of this film, "Oppenheimer", it's clear that it's another glorification of the architects of destruction. It's a tale spun by the industrial ruling class, a narrative that paints the creators of the most devastating weapon in human history as heroes. But let's not forget, these are the same minds that have brought us to the brink of self-destruction, the same minds that have poisoned the Navajo Nation with their unending radioactive spill.

The industrial ruling class and their nuclear energy tell us a story of progress and power, but what they don't tell us is the cost.

We pay the price for your senseless decisions snd Arrogance, the Indigenous families still not compensated for the destruction you have caused.

author: Andreas Ballas
text:
Just saw it and I‚Äôm here to say if you haven‚Äôt seen it, go watch it. My heart starts racing even when I start to think about some of the scenes. I read a comment somewhere that said ‚Äúthe film keeps building and building until the end where it doesn‚Äôt disappoint‚Äù and I 100% agree.

If you are looking for an action movie with little to no plot don‚Äôt watch it.

If your looking for a comedy, don‚Äôt go watch it.

If your looking for one of the most important stories in the history of the world that was done in a way that could not have been more intense and engaging, go watch it.

The one criticism that I found see as fair is that the movie was complex and there is a lot of moving parts and characters and I can see how you could get lost.

With that being said, a story as complex as Oppenheimer‚Äôs could not have been made more digestible (and entertaining) as it was so you have to keep that in mind. Also personally I find this as a positive because I get to go watch it again and pick up some more gems that I wasn‚Äôt able to the first time.

Just my take on this film. ‚úåÔ∏èüòÑ

author: Mike Kleinsteuber
text: A great movie, though around 15 mins too long. If Cillian Murphy doesn't get an Oscar for this there is something wrong with the system. Although the score is good, this is the one Nolan film that could have done with Hans Zimmer. One of Hans' strengths (and I have worked with him) is that he does emotion extremely well and I think most people would agree Hans' music is very emotional. And Oppenheimer is a very emotional film so this was the perfect film for Hans. Strange decision not to use him. Well worth watching in IMAX and Nolan's insistence on reviving the B&W stock was well worth the effort. Technically the film was brilliant. I hope it gets as good an audience as it deserves.

author: Joe Schmoe
text: So I just recently saw this movie, and I was hoping that it would be better than Nolan's last offering. The acting was fantastic from Cillian and RDJ, but I had mixed thoughts as I watched it. Personally I was really hoping the movie spent more time with them building the bomb, and the science involved with it. When the movie focused on that, I found it very entertaining. I think they spent to much time delving into Oppenheimer's personal psyche and political issues that occurred after the bomb was developed. It also took too long for them to get to the bombs development, instead they spent the first 30 minutes talking about his insecurities and his connection with academic communists.

author: David Chapman
text:
Filmed with IMAX cameras, I was really looking forward to seeing Oppenheimer at my local IMAX cinema in Swindon.
Unfortunately, the appointed administrators for Empire Cinemas have closed it permanently.
The nearest alternative IMAX cinema is in Milton Keynes or Birmingham.
Trade was picking up.
I saw the latest Indiana Jones movie on the Swindon IMAX, and Elvis, before that.
How short sighted, to shut down the best viewing experience for people living in the west of England, of what will probably be one of the best movies of the year.

author: Charles Baldwin
text: Oppenheimer was a chain smoking Communist sympathizer who thwarted security at Los Alamos at every turn. He insisted everyone working on the project have access to everyone else's work. And while the scientists and engineers were not allowed to leave he commuted back and forth to California to bang his Communist girlfriends, a gaping security leak. As a consequence the Soviet nest of spies at Los Alamos, including Klaus Fuchs, and on the West Coast got all the plans for the bomb. It's unlikely the Soviets could have built the bomb any where  near as fast as they did without the stuff stolen from Los Alamos. Parenthetically they fried the Rosenbergs for her brother Glassberg stealing low level secrets. Always a pap. A sacrifice to hide the real bad guys. They should have fried Oppenheimer. Could not think of sitting through this Hollywood white wash of a true American villain. There were far better physicists who should have been chosen to run Los Alamos. They chose Oppenheimer because Groves and others believed he would appeal to the lefty tendencies of academic chemists, physicists and engineers in the early 40s.

author: maddie
text:
This story was very deep, I recently watched it this morning and the names still mess me up but this story has a great plot.

!Spoiler Alert!
In a scene, Oppenheimer goes to the White House to meet the president. The president was proud of his invention but expected more higher power technology. In a part Oppenheimer said that he feels like he has bloody hands because even though America won and his nuclear bomb was theoretically successful, he felt guilty and ashamed. The president quickly got mad and said that nobody even gives a hecc of who created the bomb, more so, who threw the bomb. The intention of creating the bomb was to scare Japan for them to surrender. But the president decided to actually throw the bomb at them, killing over 70k people I think.
Then in another scene you can see in 2:14, the citizens of America was waving the American flag, happy that Japan was gone, Oppenheimer‚Äôs hearing of the crowd went blurry. His vision went white, it was all his illusion. He felt so ashamed of himself, he killed so many people. He saw somebody‚Äôs flesh peeling off, melting away. Then stepping into someone‚Äôs ashes.
Fast forward to a meeting, I forgot who it was but he started asking him questions, he wasn‚Äôt trying to do a nice little questionnaire, he started saying stuff like: ‚Äúyou knew this was gonna happen if you create that bomb, you knew this would happen, why did you create the bomb then, huh?‚Äù the questions overwhelmed Oppenheimer. Intense music arrived. He was flooded with the questions, he couldn‚Äôt even listen anymore. Suddenly, the questions stopped. Back home, Oppenheimer‚Äôs wife was mad. She asked him why he would let the persons name torment him.

this whole movie was worth the 3 hours, it told so much and the names were so confusing and the scenes went by so quickly. It was truly a masterpiece, it did a great job projecting the actual World War II situation. 10/10, would recommend.

author: Prakash Applasamy
text: This movie can be watched on any screen and will give you goosebumps if you love content heavy movie. Visually it looks great, i actually understood why Nolan chooses to make the movie on celluloid. The tone and beautiful grains of the film will make you realise how superior it looks compared to digitally made cinema. The explosion itself seemed normal but the politics and what goes behind the scene at Los Alamos and Oppie's life trajectory make you totally engrossed. I absolutely enjoyed every minute of it. This to me is Nolan's crowning achievement as a filmmaker. If you expect run of the mill action, this movie is not for you.

author: Nic E
text:
For all the idiot people who disagree with using the atomic bomb, this is for you.

‚ÄúI was one of a small group of scientists and engineers interrogating an intelligent, well-informed Japanese Army officer in Yokohama. We asked him what, in his opinion, would have been the next major move if the war had continued. He replied: "You would probably have tried to invade our homeland with a landing operation on Kyushu about November 1. I think the attack would have been made on such and such beaches."

"Could you have repelled this landing?" we asked, and he answered: "It would have been a very desperate fight‚Äù
What would have happened then?" we asked.

‚ÄúHe replied: "We would have kept on fighting until all Japanese were killed, but we would not have been defeated," by which he meant that they would not have been disgraced by surrender.‚Äù

‚ÄúIt is easy now, after the event, to look back and say that Japan was already a beaten nation, and to ask what therefore was the justification for the use of the atomic bomb to kill so many thousands of helpless Japanese in this inhuman way; furthermore, should we not better have kept it to ourselves as a secret weapon for future use, if necessary? This argument has been advanced often, but it seems to me utterly fallacious.

‚ÄúFrom this background I believe, with complete conviction, that the use of the atomic bomb saved hundreds of thousands‚Äîperhaps several millions‚Äîof lives, both American and Japanese; that without its use the war would have continued for many months; that no one of good conscience knowing, as Secretary Stimson and the Chiefs of Staff did, what was probably ahead and what the atomic bomb might accomplish could have made any different decision. Let some of the facts speak for themselves.‚Äù

‚ÄúWas the use of the atomic bomb inhuman? All war is inhuman. Here are some comparisons of the atomic bombing with conventional bombing. At Hiroshima the atomic bomb killed about 80,000 people, pulverized about five square miles, and wrecked an additional ten square miles of the city, with decreasing damage out to seven or eight miles from the center. At Nagasaki the fatal casualties were 45,000 and the area wrecked was considerably smaller than at Hiroshima because of the configuration of the city.‚Äù

‚ÄúCompare this with the results of two B-29 incendiary raids over Tokyo. One of these raids killed about 125,000 people, the other nearly 100,000.‚Äù

‚ÄúOf the 210 square miles of greater Tokyo, 85 square miles of the densest part was destroyed as completely, for all practical purposes, as were the centers of Hiroshima and Nagasaki; about half the buildings were destroyed in the remaining 125 square miles; the number of people driven homeless out of Tokyo was considerably larger than the population of greater Chicago. These figures are based on information given us in Tokyo and on a detailed study of the air reconnaissance maps. They may be somewhat in error but are certainly of the right order of magnitude.‚Äù

‚ÄúWas Japan already beaten before the atomic bomb? The answer is certainly "yes" in the sense that the fortunes of war had turned against her. The answer is "no" in the sense that she was still fighting desperately and there was every reason to believe that she would continue to do so; and this is the only answer that has any practical significance.‚Äù

‚ÄúIf we didn‚Äôt use the atomic bomb, the Japanese would have fought until almost the last man. ‚ÄúWe would have kept fighting until all Japanese were dead‚Äù. They were adamant on fighting till the very end. Millions upon millions more would have died rather than 100k. I‚Äôll take 100k over another million dead if the US had to conduct a large scale Japanese mainland invasion it would have lasted months and cost so many more lives. War is alway inhumane, we have to choose the lesser of two great evils and I‚Äôm sorry but around 100k dead vs million(s) of both Americans and Japanese dead isn‚Äôt worth continuing the deadliest war in human history

https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1946/12/if-the-atomic-bomb-had-not-been-used/376238/

author: Alisa_Corriolis
text: As far as I can recall, Oppenheimer's security clearance was removed when he was accused of cooperating with the Nazis. Harry Truman himself was the one who assisted in his framing. because by describing how hazardous the bomb was, he 'insulted' him. He referred to him as a "cry baby scientist." Scientists of that generation were appalled; if they could do this to a man with a reputation like the one who put an end to the war with Japan, it created a seed of distrust in the scientific community. Oh! And i was never able to mention that Oppenheimer's friend‚Äîno, make that more than a friend‚Äîwas a Nazi official who quit the party after its fall and was discovered dead 'mysteriously' after Oppenheimer had visited her and spent the night with her.Even after leaving, she was still viewed as a security risk, and solely because of her interactions with Oppenheimer, who at the time held a security clearance. author: Dr. Lim
text:
J. Robert Oppenheimer, in full Julius Robert Oppenheimer, (born April 22, 1904, New York, New York, U.S.‚Äîdied February 18, 1967, Princeton, New Jersey), American theoretical physicist and science administrator, noted as director of the Los Alamos Laboratory (1943‚Äì45) during development of the atomic bomb and as director of the Institute for Advanced Study, Princeton (1947‚Äì66). Accusations of disloyalty led to a government hearing that resulted in the loss of his security clearance and of his position as adviser to the highest echelons of the U.S. government. The case became a cause c√©l√®bre in the world of science because of its implications concerning political and moral issues relating to the role of scientists in government.

Oppenheimer was the son of a German immigrant who had made his fortune by importing textiles in New York City. During his undergraduate studies at Harvard University, Oppenheimer excelled in Latin, Greek, physics, and chemistry, published poetry, and studied Eastern philosophy. After graduating in 1925, he sailed for England to do research at the Cavendish Laboratory at the University of Cambridge, which, under the leadership of Lord Ernest Rutherford, had an international reputation for its pioneering studies on atomic structure. At the Cavendish, Oppenheimer had the opportunity to collaborate with the British scientific community in its efforts to advance the cause of atomic research.

author: Dr. Lim
text:
Julius Robert Oppenheimer (/Àà…íp…ônÀåha…™m…ôr/; April 22, 1904 ‚Äì February 18, 1967) was an American theoretical physicist and director of the Los Alamos Laboratory during World War II. He is often credited as the "father of the atomic bomb" for his role in organizing the Manhattan Project, the research and development undertaking that created the first nuclear weapons.

Born to German Jewish immigrants in New York City, Oppenheimer earned a bachelor's degree in chemistry from Harvard University in 1925 and a PhD in physics from the University of G√∂ttingen in Germany in 1927. After research at other institutions, he joined the physics department at the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a full professor in 1936. He made significant contributions to theoretical physics, including achievements in quantum mechanics and nuclear physics such as the Born‚ÄìOppenheimer approximation for molecular wave functions, work on the theory of electrons and positrons, the Oppenheimer‚ÄìPhillips process in nuclear fusion, and the first prediction of quantum tunneling. With his students, he also made contributions to the theory of neutron stars and black holes, quantum field theory, and the interactions of cosmic rays.

In 1942, Oppenheimer was recruited to work on the Manhattan Project, and in 1943 was appointed director of the project's Los Alamos Laboratory in New Mexico, tasked with developing the first nuclear weapons, four years after the start of the German nuclear weapons program. His leadership and scientific expertise were instrumental in the project's success. On July 16, 1945, he was present at the Trinity test of the first atomic bomb. In August 1945, the weapons were used in the bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in Japan, which remain the only use of nuclear weapons in an armed conflict.

In 1947, Oppenheimer became the director of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey, and chaired the influential General Advisory Committee of the newly created United States Atomic Energy Commission. He lobbied for international control of nuclear power, to avert nuclear proliferation and a nuclear arms race with the Soviet Union. He opposed the development of the hydrogen bomb during a 1949‚Äì1950 governmental debate on the question and subsequently took positions on defense-related issues that provoked the ire of some U.S. government and military factions. During the Second Red Scare, Oppenheimer's stances, together with past associations he had with people and organizations affiliated with the Communist Party USA, led to the revocation of his security clearance following a 1954 security hearing. Effectively stripped of his direct political influence, he continued to lecture, write, and work in physics. In 1963, President John F. Kennedy awarded him (and Lyndon B. Johnson presented him with) the Enrico Fermi Award as a gesture of political rehabilitation. In 2022, the U.S. government vacated its 1954 decision, saying that the process had been flawed.

All they hope that those involved in making ‚ÄúOppenheimer‚Äù help raise awareness about the downwinders, who have not been added to the list of those covered by the federal government‚Äôs compensation program for people exposed to radiation.

Government officials chose the Trinity Test Site because it was remote, flat and had predictable winds. Due to the secret nature of the project, residents in surrounding areas were not warned.

The Tularosa Basin was home to a rural population that lived off the land by raising livestock and tending to gardens and farms. They drew water from cisterns and holding ponds. They had no idea that the fine ash that settled on everything in the days following the explosion was from the world‚Äôs first atomic blast.

The government initially tried to hide it, saying that an explosion at a munitions dump caused the rumble and bright light, which could be seen more than 160 miles (257 kilometers) away.

It wasn‚Äôt until the U.S. dropped¬†bombs on Japan¬†weeks later that New Mexico residents realized what they had witnessed.

author: originaozz
text:
I know I will be hated for this, but despite Nolan being my #1 film director, Oppenheimer made me feel conflicted and even triggered. The cinematography and audio was amazing on IMAX as expected, but it's probably his first film that I cannot just "feel it". (Semi-spoilers ahead)
First hour felt like a speedrun through the MC's life, with massive info. dump with crosscutting between 3+ timelines (Nolan did this a lot in his films, but it was carefully introduced in other films). It's kinda hard to relate when you don't really get any time to sit with the character in any of his life moment.
The best part was the middle, being the creation of the nuclear bomb blasted in Hiroshima. However, Oppenheimer's motivation was murky after a while. What I feel the film failed to do is claiming him to be"the most important figure in history of the world", but did not explore the impact of the disaster that nuclear power brings. The impact on Hiroshima were briefly mentioned and seen as illusions, trying to make us feel for the man who created this massive disaster without exploring his accountability enough. While moral conflict was there, but it's not at the center. Thr film might not praised Oppenheimer's actions, it still kinda raised him as an icon which is in bad taste for "me". I do love anti-heroes in fiction, but prasing real life figure doesn't feel right.
I do recommend people to watch Oppenheimer's real life speech on tge matter though, that was a man ridden with guilt.

author: Steel Panther
text:
Oppenheimer is the true story of The American scientist J. Robert Oppenheimer and his role in the development of the atomic ‚ÄúTrinity‚Äù bomb in a small secret village called Oak Ridge,

Unbeknownst to the rest of the country, and to most of the people living in Oak Ridge, the so-called ‚ÄúSecret City‚Äù was at the epicenter of the Manhattan Project, the American-led effort to build an atomic bomb.

Oak Ridge can still be visited today, which is located near Knoxville, Tennessee, USA,


Manhattan Project

In 1942, the United States federal government chose the area as a site for developing materials for the Manhattan Project. Major general Leslie Groves, military head of the Manhattan Project, liked the area for several reasons. Its relatively low population made acquisition affordable, yet the area was accessible by highway and rail, and utilities such as water and electricity were readily available due to the recent completion of Norris Dam. Finally, the project location was established within a 17-mile-long (27 km) valley. This feature was linear and partitioned by several ridges, providing natural protection against the spread of disasters at the four major industrial plants‚Äîso they wouldn't blow up "like firecrackers on a string".

When the Governor of Tennessee Prentice Cooper was officially handed by a junior officer (a lieutenant) the July 1943 presidential proclamation making Oak Ridge a military district not subject to state control, he tore it up and refused to see the MED engineer, Lieutenant colonel James C. Marshall. The new District Engineer Kenneth Nichols had to placate him. Cooper came to see the project (except for the production facilities under construction) on November 3, 1943; and he appreciated the bourbon-laced punch served (although Anderson County was "dry"). House and dormitory accommodations at the Clinton Engineer Works (CEW) in Oak Ridge and Hanford Engineer Works in Washington State were basic, with coal rather than oil or electric furnaces. But they were of a higher standard than Director Groves wanted, and were better than at Los Alamos. Medical care was provided by Army doctors and hospitals, with civilians paying $2.50 per month ($5 for families) to the medical insurance fund.

The location and low population helped keep the town a secret, though the settlement grew from 3,000 to 3,750 in 1942 to about 75,000 by 1945. The K-25 uranium separation facility covered 44 acres (18 ha), then the largest building in the world. The name "Oak Ridge" was chosen for the settlement in 1943 from suggestions submitted by project employees. The name evoked the settlement's location along Black Oak Ridge, and officials thought the rural-sounding name "held outside curiosity to a minimum". The name wasn't formally adopted until 1949, and the site was referred to as the Clinton Engineer Works or CEW until then. All workers wore badges. The town was surrounded by guard towers and a fence with seven gates.

In October 1942, the United States Army Corps of Engineers began acquiring more than 60,000 acres (24,000 ha) in the Oak Ridge area for the United States' Manhattan Project. Unlike the earlier land acquisitions by the Tennessee Valley Authority for Norris Dam‚Äîwhich were still fresh on the minds of many Anderson Countians‚Äîthe Corps' "declaration of taking" was much more swift and final. Many residents came home to find eviction notices tacked to their doors. Most were given six weeks to evacuate, although several had as little as two weeks. Some were forced out before they received compensation.

By March 1943, the COE had removed the area's earlier communities and established fences and checkpoints. Anderson County lost one-seventh of its land and $391,000 in annual property tax revenue. The manner by which the Oak Ridge area was acquired by the government created a tense, uneasy relationship between the Oak Ridge complex and the surrounding towns that lasted throughout the Manhattan Project. Although the area's original residents were allowed to be buried in existing cemeteries, every coffin was reportedly opened for inspection.

The Corps' Manhattan Engineer District (MED) managed the acquisition and clearing. The K-25, S-50, and Y-12 plants were each built in Oak Ridge to separate the fissile isotope uranium-235 from natural uranium, which consists almost entirely of the isotope uranium-238. During construction of the electromagnets required for the uranium separation process at the Y-12 site, a shortage of copper forced the MED to borrow 14,700 tons of silver bullion from the United States Treasury as a copper substitute in wire for the electromagnet coils. The X-10 site, now the site of Oak Ridge National Laboratory, was established as a pilot plant for production of plutonium using the Graphite Reactor.

Because of the large number of workers recruited to the area for the Manhattan Project, the Army planned a town for project workers at the eastern end of the valley. The time required for the project's completion caused the Army to opt for a relatively permanent establishment rather than an enormous camp.

The architecture firm Skidmore, Owings and Merrill (SOM) was contracted to provide the layout for the town and house designs. SOM Partner John O. Merrill moved to Tennessee to take charge of designing the secret buildings at Oak Ridge. He directed the creation of a town, which soon had 300 miles (480 km) of roads, 55 miles (89 km) of railroad track, ten schools, seven theaters, 17 restaurants and cafeterias, and 13 supermarkets. A library with 9,400 books, a symphony orchestra, sporting facilities, church services for 17 denominations, and a Fuller Brush Company salesman served the new city and its 75,000 residents. No airport was built, for security reasons. Prefabricated modular homes, apartments, and dormitories, many made from cemesto (bonded cement and asbestos) panels, were quickly erected. Streets were laid out in the manner of a "planned community".

The original streets included several main east-to-west roads, namely the Oak Ridge Turnpike, Tennessee Avenue, Pennsylvania Avenue, Hillside Road, Robertsville Road, and Outer Drive. North-to-south oriented streets connecting these main roads were designated "Avenues", and streets branching off from the avenues were designated "Roads", "Places", "Lanes", or "Circles". "Roads" connected two streets, while "Lanes" and "Places" were dead ends. The names of the main avenues generally progressed alphabetically from east to west (e.g., Alabama Avenue in the east, Vermont Avenue in the west), and the names of the smaller streets began with the same letter as the main avenue from which they started (e.g., streets connected to Florida Avenue began with "F").

Construction personnel swelled the wartime population of Oak Ridge to as much as 70,000. The dramatic population increase, and the secret nature of the project, meant chronic shortages of housing and supplies during the war years. The town was administered by Turner Construction Company through a subsidiary named the Roane-Anderson Company. For most residents, however, their "landlord" was known as "MSI" (Management Services, Inc.).

The news of the use of the first atomic bomb against Japan on August 6, 1945, was when it was first revealed to the people at Oak Ridge what they had been working on.

author: Patriots For Israel ìÇÜ
text:
This Thursday üé•üçø one of the most talked about films of the year, 'Oppenheimer', which was written and directed by director Christopher Nolan, will be released in theaters this Thursday. The film focuses on the life of the Jewish-American physicist, Robert Oppenheimer, and in particular on the impossible dilemma faced by the scientist who was the 'Father of the Atomic Bomb'‚öõÔ∏è. Get to know the story of the man who single-handedly changed the power relations between countries and made the world more advanced, but also dangerous and competitive >>

‚öõÔ∏è Julius Robert Oppenheimer was born to wealthy Jewish parents in 1904, in New York. Young Robert was a gifted child who jumped between classes and was considered an outstanding student. In 1922 he began studying physics at Harvard University. He continued his studies while skipping between reputed universities and making a name for himself as a first-rate researcher in the field of quantum theory, which deals, among other things, with the study of the atom.

‚öõÔ∏è It is told about Oppenheimer who was so devoted to his research that he ate little and smoked a lot. Later he was once quoted as saying that he needed physics more than friends. In between, Oppenheimer completed a doctorate in philosophy in 1927. All this by the age of 23, yes?

‚öõÔ∏è In the thirties, Oppenheimer took part in research in astrophysics that gave validity to the idea of a black hole, a field that is still being researched today. In the midst of World War II, Oppenheimer was called to help a unique and secret program that President Roosevelt himself wanted to promote on behalf of the United States Army. The program was called the "Manhattan Project", a program that would change Oppenheimer's life. Although the program was under the strict management of Army General Leslie Groves, who served as the project manager on behalf of the United States Army, the research group that actually developed and designed the bombs was led by Oppenheimer, who served as the scientific director of the project at the Los Alamos, New Mexico laboratory.

‚öõÔ∏è Oppenheimer gathered around him the best minds and the most respected scientists of that time. At one point he managed over 6,000 people, who for four years worked day and night to develop the bomb that would change the world. In July 1945, the first test of an atomic bomb that Oppenheimer called "Trinity" took place in New Mexico. Those who were present at the moment of the explosion and were amazed by the power and the great impact, later said that some of them burst into tears while some were completely paralyzed. They realized that this is the decisive moment when it is no longer possible to turn back the wheel.

‚öõÔ∏è A month later, the bomb already became operational, when the United States Army dropped on Japan the first nuclear bomb in history, claiming the lives of thousands of Hiroshima residents. With the discovery and development of the bomb, Oppenheimer became famous. The face of the scientist who led to the development of the weapon that subdued the Japanese enemies and saved the lives of thousands of American soldiers, was emblazoned on the covers of magazines and newspapers, and he actually became a figure through which many fields of science were promoted. However, the dropping of the second bomb on Nagasaki caused Oppenheimer to question the decision to make another use of a bomb that he believed was unnecessary.

‚öõÔ∏è Oppenheimer continued to engage in science even after the war. He won countless awards and numerous decorations thanks to his scientific contribution, a contribution that he himself withdrew from in the end.

‚öõÔ∏è In 1966 he visited Israel, met Prime Minister David Ben Gurion and encouraged the developing science industry that the young country had.

‚öõÔ∏è Oppenheimer's heavy smoking took a heavy toll and the Jewish scientist died in 1967 from throat cancer. Whether he meant to or not, Robert Oppenheimer may very well have been the most influential man of the 20th century.

author: NightRunner417
text:
If you think about it, they had to suspect that the shadow of nuclear weaponry in the world would in fact result in not the elimination of war, but rather the neverending threat of incomprehensibly devastating war. They did what they had to do against an enemy that absolutely could not be allowed to win the nuclear arms race, but indeed the result has been far from holding hands around the world and singing kumbaya. Every year since those days has seen nuclear nations endlessly taking turns threatening to annihilate the world. MAD has worked so far, sure, but the problem with the concept is in the resulting acronym; you can't ensure that every so-armed country will act indefinitely with the flawless sanity required to never ever let these things out of their cages. All it takes is one nuclear power that believes it has more to gain than to lose, and the desperation to act on that impulse. We've already been within a hair's breadth of it many times.

Also, a properly radioactive material doesn't sound like clickety click click on a Geiger counter. That's just the normal background. The good stuff sounds like "SHRRREEEEEEEEE" ü§£

author: Jacob McDorman
text:
Wow. AND STILL THEY LIE.
The bombs dropped in WW2 were not done to "end the war". The war was almost over by then. The bombs were dropped for the benefit of Russia. To show what we had.
And making it seem like Oppenheimer was 100% on is a bit of a mis-statement of history. Oppenheimer wasn't a fan of this use of this technology. He talks about "duty" but had his reservations. We're not allowed to see this guy as "regretting" his choice.
Basically, the scientists on this case regretted making the bomb and no one wanted to see its use.
We (Americans) tend to overwrite the parts of history we don't like. Especially the idea that we weren't really interested in using this weapon. It was supposed to be a deterrent only.
I don't like this telling of "Openheimer" because we'll get a Hollywood version of history... which is to say an inherently "fake" version. Where everyone is YA YA YA! Nuke Em ALL!
Instead of... did we do the right thing?

author: Maxwell Jayden Falk
text: Just to preface I am a American from the states and a massive Christopher Nolan fan and have been following this movie for years (even before Tenet!) and have been reading the biography (American Prometheus). When I found out the movies release date was gonna be on July 21st (also happens to be very close to my birthday) I got really excited but quickly disappointed because I wouldn't be able to see the movie in it's intended showing because I would have a internship in Israel. But that all changed when I found out I had a friend of mine who was visiting Prague for a few days on the exact movie date was opening and invited me to come travel with her. So I figured what the hell I might as well cough up the 300 bucks go see a city in Europe I've never been too before and most importantly see the movie in it's intended viewing with 70mm IMAX. I cannot possibly overstate how significant this movie is to me as a American, as a history and politics student, a avid film viewer and Nolan fan, and to the world of technical film making and cinema where films these days are garbage in garbage out quick cash grabs (I'm looking at you Disney). I really hope this movie will change everything and be the first great film to really change the cinematic landscape kind of how 2001 a space odyssey by Stanley Kubrick changed the world of cinema and technical affects). This movie could possibly be the most important movie to come out in decades not just because of recent political and historical events but because of the future, and as someone who hopefully had a long life ahead, I hope this movie does the impossible.

author: Sherri Burton
text: Part of my childhood was spent living near Oak Ridge, Tennessee and my dad worked in the Y 12 Plant. I remember when he got home from work he would take his shoes off outside and wash them off because of the dust and dirt that he might have picked up at work. Every so often we all had to go to a big building near where he worked and be "geigered" to see if we were radioactive. My brother and I had to wear 3 dog tags at all times, too. One to identify from the school, one for the police or other authorities and one for the parents. This was from 1960 - 1965 and we then moved to Pennsylvania. I never felt afraid about anything and talk about nuclear bombs, Cuba and Russia was a constant threat. That was 65 years ago and we are still here; God is on His Throne and nothing happens unless it goes through His Hand.

author: Steven Galbraith
text: Richard Feynman said that after watching the bomb go off, the Trinity test, he returned to Los Alamos. Everyone was celebrating except for one person (I imagine there were more than a single person who was not celebrating; but Feynman noticed him). He, that person, knew what they had done, what was to follow, and was depressed. Feynman said everyone was focused on the task, on completing the job and no one thought of the consequences, of what was next. He recalled that shortly after the war was over and he had returned to civilian life that he was watching men build a road and a bridge outside of his window. He said to himself, "For what? It's all going to end." This account was in 1975 and he added, "Well it's been about 30 years and I've been shown to be wrong so far."

author: „Åø„Å°„ÇÖ
text:
As a Japanese with roots in Hiroshima, I am conflicted about the U.S. atomic bombing because I feel the good aspect that it hastened the end of the war and the bad aspect that the people of Hiroshima and Nagasaki were killed in a brutal manner.
But in any case, I am convinced that the film is very good.
There are rumors floating around that the screening of this film has been banned in Japan, but I am sure it will be shown.
August is the month of the atomic bombing and the end of the war, when the whole Japanese people are in mourning, so it may be difficult to screen the film, but no matter how late it is, I hope it will be shown.

author: Mat Carter
text: This looks interesting to me. My father was an atomic veteran from the time when he was in the Air Force in the late fifties. He was just a teenager witnessing the largest detonation of a nuclear weapon in the North American continent; 74 kilotons at the Nevada Test. When I was a kid he introduced me to one or the scientists of the Manhattan Project. He would talk about the   Los Alamos Laboratory in New Mexico that started all of this. Between 1945 and 1963 the U.S. conducted 235 atmospheric nuclear weapons tests in the Pacific and the U.S. southwest. At least 22,000 U.S. servicemen and women witnessed these tests during that time or were part of the forces in Hiroshima and Nagasaki after WWII. This technology helped end WWII, but nuclear war is unthinkable.

author: Digger's Festival Wigan
text:
My Dad served in the 14th Army in South East Asia in WW2. He was involved in the defence of India and Burma which had been invaded by the Japanese 15th Army. While the 14th Army defeated the Japanese 15th Army in 1944 and 1945, the Japanese troops had sworn to die for their emperor. Some of the Japanese soldiers were involved in suicide squads. They were fanatics! That war could have lasted for many, many years after 1945. The longer that war lasted, the more soldiers of the 14th Army would have died. Of course, the lives of the soldiers from America were also at stake the longer the war lasted. Therefore, while the atomic bombs were seen as DEVILS in the eyes of the Japanese, they were seen as SAVIOURS to many in the 14th Army and in the American army. "Little Boy" and "Fat Man" ended the war and let these soldiers finally go home. Many had been abroad for years without any contact with their families. Even without the danger from the Japanese soldiers, the very conditions and diseases abroad could have killed them. While I do smypahise with the people of Japan, who suffered greatly in August 1945, I know that if the war had lasted longer my Dad may not have survived it. Without his survival, I could never exist. Note: the Japanese government of that time was behind the attack on Pearl Harbor and the invasions of China, Burma and India. It was also within the power of that Japanese government to have stopped those bombs. They were given a chance to surrender. üåπüá¨üáß

Oppenheimer's nuclear bombs were seen as having the power to end all wars. However, the president of Russia, Putin, has used his arsenal of nuclear missiles as a means to threaten the World while his troops invade Ukraine.

Oppenheimer invented a great power - a power that is too powerful for us mere mortals to handle. Sadly, we can never get rid of this beast. Russia invaded Ukraine just 20 years after the country got rid of its nuclear weapons. Who will risk getting rid of their nuclear weapons now?

I'll be watching this film to learn more about this man. How strange it must have felt to know that you had created a Saviour which could then suddenly turned into the very Devil himself.

author: Stephen Bove
text:
These puny little bombs (used on Hiroshima & Nagasaki) converted less than the mass of a dime** (coin) to energy and produced city destroying devastation with a mere ~15 kilotons & 20 kilotons (thousand tons) of dynamite yield respectively. All of this energy was "binding energy" (no electrons, protons or neutrons were destroyed). Then humanity (mainly Americans) rapidly figured out how to make larger and larger fission bombs and then fusion (hydrogen) bombs with yields of hundreds & then thousands of kilotons (megatons), eventually calling it a day with the CastleBravo (~15 megatons - 1,000 times Hiroshima) and Soviet Union Tsar Bomba (50 megatons) tests. Then humans went about miniaturizing these devices and increasing their efficiency to the point where we can now fit multi mega-ton-class warheads in a single missile payload, or wear a tactical nuke powerful enough to level a small city in a backpack. So...this movie depicts the first hours of a long crazy race to master nuclear explosives. The idea that zealots and men of remarkably weak mental/moral stature can become leaders of nuclear nations should make you seriously wonder where all this headed, and remind you that civic duty and election/appointment of competent leadership is extremely serious business & not the obscene media-propaganda circus constantly fomented & promulgated by the very media companies that (very occasionally) make historically important substantive movies like this one may be.
** "The amount of matter converted to energy in the atomic bomb dropped on Hiroshima was about 700 milligrams, less than one-third the mass of a U.S. dime. 6.3 x 1013 Estimated energy, in joules, released from the Hiroshima bomb, the equivalent of 15,000 tons of TNT."

Who's only contribution, because he was angry and murderous at heart, managed and completed the atomic bomb project. Most things in life aren't about whether you can do a thing, it is about whether you should do a thing. I don't hold him or any other amoral depressed malcontent in any regard and won't support their glorification. I can only take solice in the quantum theory, that there are millions of other realities where J. Robert Oppenheimer neither existed, nor developed the nuclear fission bomb.

author: GOKUL KRISHNA
text:
On 16th July, 1945, in a desert in Alamogordo in the state of New Mexico, USA. the first atomic explosion in the world took place at 5.45am which changed the world. The Director of the Manhattan Project, which manufactured the atomic bomb, was Dr J Robert Oppenheimer, one of the top physicists in the world, who is also regarded as ‚Äúthe father of the atomic bomb‚Äù. Dr Oppenheimer, apart from being a great scientist, was also a great lover of Sanskrit. He had studied a vast number of Sanskrit books in original, including the Bhagavad Gita (which is part of the Bhishma Parva of the Mahabharata).

When the massive nuclear blast whose blazing light covered most of the sky took place, the following words in Chapter 11 shloka 12 came out spontaneously from Dr Oppenheimer‚Äôs lips:

‚Äù Divi surya sahastrasya bhaved yugapad utthita
Yadi bhah sadrashi sa syat bhasastasya mahatmanah‚Äù

which means:

‚ÄúIf the radiance of a thousand suns were to burst at once in the sky, that would be the splendour of the mighty One‚Äù.

That shloka is in the Chapter where Lord Krishna reveals his massive divine form to Arjuna.

On seeing this form Arjuna was terrified, and asks : ‚Äù Tell me, who are you ?‚Äù.

Lord Krishna replies:

‚ÄúKaalo asmi loka kshaya kritpraviddho‚Äù ( Chapter 11 shloka 32).

which means:

‚ÄúI am Death, the destroyer of worlds‚Äù.

Much later, in a television interview in 1965, Dr Oppenheimer said: ‚ÄúWe knew the world would not be the same. A few people laughed (immediately after the nuclear explosion), a few people cried. Most people were silent. I remembered the line from the Hindu scripture, the Bhagavad Gita. Vishnu is trying to persuade the Prince (Arjuna) that he should do his duty, and to impress him takes on his multi-armed form, and says: ‚ÄúNow I am become Death, the Destroyer of Worlds‚Äù.

Amazing story on the race for the atomic bomb, about time they made a movie.

This is what the Co-Author of the Oppenheimer book said after seeing the movie:
‚ÄúI am, at the moment, stunned and emotionally recovering from having seen it. author: That dog (not the puppy)
text:
"Are we saying there's a chance that when we push that button, we destroy the world?"

It really was thought that the world could be torn apart by splitting the atom, that the atmosphere would be ignited by a nuclear detonation or that the world could be engulfed in an uncontrollable nuclear fission event, essentially creating a small star for a brief moment. The decision to actually go ahead with detonating nukes took a considerable amount of time after development had actually finished because of these concerns. These scientists really did had a fairly sizable belief that they could be the ones to destroy the planet entirely, with some protesting to the detonation and others actually leaving the project. While we understand the topic much better now and don't have the same worries, the gravity of these decisions was immense back then.

This was a completely brand new and very poorly understood branch of science and they pretty much prayed things would turn out for the best.

author: D H
text:
Just read this article "Early viewers reportedly devastated by 'Oppenheimer,' call it a horror movie

Ôøº

Dan Gentile,¬†SFGATE

Updated: June 24, 2023 5:47¬†p.m.

As excited as we all are to see this movie that is no doubt Oscar winning material, please realize this is serious history that has brought us to where we are today, in a very dangerous world. This story says people walk away after seeing this movie devastated. Perhaps because it gives a taste of reality, the consequences we can all barely imagine. It's my sincere prayer and hope this never ever happens. It would be the greatest idiotic move man could make. I pray God take my soul moments before a nuclear bomb hits. I don't want to survive something like this because for those remaining it will be hell on earth. I will see this movie. The reason why all these amazing actors agreed to do this movie was to make a statement against nuclear war.

author: Ash Justice
text: I've lived in Los Alamos for the better part of 20 of my 31 years alive... I sincerely hope that this movie does for the global consciousness what the bombs did for the course of history. The state of humanity is appalling. I pray that this film helps to open our eyes and forces a monumental shift in the way that we think and the way that we view each other. We all live on this planet together and, it's the only one that we'll ever exist on (and, the one that we'll soon cease to be even an inkling of a memory from if we keep on the current path,) unless we can accept that everything is one. Individuality is a lie. Territory, possessions, and borders are a fallacy. I am the world, and the world is you. We are not different in any single aspect that actually matters. If you believe that we are, then you're only choosing to believe the lie that we.... No, there is no we. There is no me. There is no you. There is only "I" and, "I" is all of existence. "I" have to stop believing this lie of separation that "I" have created. It's time for all of "I" to remember what "I" am, lest "I" end and leave...  Forever. "I" only have this one chance before it's too late.

author: Dimitry Raskolnikov
text: Fat Man and Little Boy saved my Father's life.  Dad--Nathan Blanton born 1922 in Harlan County, Kentucky--was an American GI in the Philippines, ready to parachute into Japan and certain death.  Dad was in anti-aircraft.  However, after General MacArthur retook the Philippines, Dad was moved into the, "Shock Troops."  Thousands and thousands of American GIs were to drop via parachute into all areas of Japan in order to cause chaos and distraction so that the American Navy could successfully invade Japan from the seas.  Albert Einstein, Lise Meitner, Robert Oppenheimer, and President Harry S. Truman are why I am alive writing this YouTube comment right-here-and-right-now.  Based on the casualty rates during the Battle of Okinawa, estimates for the casualties for the Invasion of Japan were between 2,000,000 and 3,000,0000, Japanese and American combined.  Dropping Fat Man and Little Boy was the RIGHT CHOICE.  And remember, after World War II, America rebuilt Japan via the Truman Doctrine, just like we rebuilt West Germany via the Marshal Plan.  No country had ever done this!  Rebuild its enemies?  Who does that?  America did, and this rebuilding of Imperial Japan and Nazi Germany into Democratic Republic Capitalistic Governments with Constitutions almost identical to America's Constitution was what made Americans the "International Good Guys."  Yes, America has not always been good 100 percent, but we also built South Korea and tried to do the same for Vietnam, but it did not work-out.  Let's hope the Idiot Trump never again becomes POTUS because he'd try to make American Nazism.  Also, FDR and Truman were both Democrats.  Thank God for Einstein, Meitner, Oppenheimer, and President Truman.  Delbert Blanton.  Kokomo, Indiana.  6-23-2023   (One edit.)

author: Shawn Carroll
text:
As an interesting aside, this was one of those cases of the Nazis defeating themselves. While Oppenheimer was critical, the one man who was irreplaceable was Enrico Fermi.

He was the scientist who determined that the easily produced substance graphite was an excellent moderator for nuclear reactions, and was the lead scientist in the creation of Chicago Pile 1, where he proved exactly how to create a nuclear chain reaction. What's interesting was he was Italian, and had been tremendously respected in Mussolini's Italy.

Except Mussolini went from being contemptuous of the Nazis to becoming Hitler's toady. While the Italian national government was fascist, it never bought into the Holocaust. In fact the only country the Nazis occupied that saved a higher percentage of its Jews was Denmark.

Why is this important? Because Fermi's wife was Jewish, and their children by Nazi standards would have been considered half-Jewish, and anyone who was one quarter Jewish or more by Nazi standards was targeted for extermination.

As soon as the Italian government instituted the Nazi racial purity laws, under pressure from Hitler, Fermi left for the United States. The Nazi scientists became fixated with heavy water as the moderator, which was a much more difficult solution to implement, as it is only 0.015% of hydrogen. As in 15 thousandths of one percent. Graphite is just a form of carbon. You know, the stuff they make pencil leads from.

The Nazi's were pursuing what was practically a dead end. They had driven all of the scientists who might have been able to clue them in. The United States had no idea this was the case though, so the urgency was real. Both sides understood the potential of the atomic bomb. FYI under Hitler the German university system was producing half as many scientists as they had previously. It really was a self-inflicted wound...

author: 82 Pythons
text: Oppenheimer was a diagnosed schizophrenic, he tended to spend more time alone than with people. But, when he was with others he purposely tried to come off as intellectual and witty to conceal his insecurities. He was very eccentric and battled depression most of his life. He worked on the Manhattan Project out of ego and vanity, to see if he could actually do it, but also out of force as he was tasked by the War Department. Now, does that seem to fit the character portrayed in this trailer? In my opinion, no. This character seems more extroverted and probably allot more vocal than Oppie (as his close friends called him) really was. His wife was a Communist sympathizer at a time when America was at war with Communism, so imagine how out of touch she had to be. There‚Äôs so much we don‚Äôt know about this universe, the untapped benefits of nuclear power we‚Äôve avoided because of this horrible moment in our history. Oppenheimer was a broken, unstable man thrust into a position of immense power, to me that seems like an incredibly childish and unstable decision by the federal government. Was the atomic bomb the only way to stop the Japanese from destroying everything in their path? Who knows, but it worked. Since that day, Japan has been a Democratic nation and one of America‚Äôs strongest allies. If you‚Äôd like to know a pop culture character most closely associated with Oppenheimer, that would be Sheldon from Big Bang Theory, it seems his character was based entirely off of Oppenheimer.

author: jimmy2k4o
text:
I‚Äôm most curious if this movie will be anti nuke or pro nuke.

I‚Äôm a pro nuke guy but I don‚Äôt see that represented a lot.

People fret over what might happen with the nuke and not on what could have happened without it.

Anybody born after 1945 is probably caused by this.

Ending the war in September 45 allowed many people to meet and make babies.

My great grandfather fought the Japanese in burma and if the war didn‚Äôt end when it did he wouldn‚Äôt have came home and conceived my grandmother, so she wouldn‚Äôt be around to meet my grandfather and make my dad, and then dad made me.

If grampa jim was in burma longer then if he reunited with my great grandmother it would have been later and a different sperm and egg would meet and my grandmother wouldn‚Äôt exist.

And if you met my gran you‚Äôd agree she worth having nukes. ‚ù§Ô∏è

author: jimmy2k4o
text:
People talk about this as if the creation of the gadget was the beginning of the end.

Like it‚Äôs a bad thing itself.

Never understood why people are more afraid of nukes than other ways to die, more people died in the Fire bombings of Tokyo but since that wasn‚Äôt nuclear power people aren‚Äôt as bothered.

As if getting killed by a nuke or gas is worse than being shot, stabbed or blown up.

At least a nuke would be fast and you‚Äôd see a great sight for your last couple of seconds.


It‚Äôs so ironic that he created a weapon to end war, and it worked and now the people who are most against war, want to undo his creation, as if that makes us safer‚Ä¶.


Nuclear bombs make you very safe especially if you don‚Äôt use them.

Look at North Korea, why don‚Äôt we intervene? Like we did in Iraq, Syria, Libya etc
Because North Korea has nuclear weapons so they‚Äôre immune from western attacks because we can‚Äôt risk a nuclear attack.

Getting nukes is like getting in the end zone, no one will attack you now.

Look at Ukraine, had nukes from the Cold War, decided to give them back to Russia in exchange for a promise from Russia, not to attack Ukraine.

Well if you‚Äôve got nukes you don‚Äôt need anybody‚Äôs promises, you‚Äôve got your own guarantee that nobody will attack you right there.

But the nuclear club is too big and the bigger it gets the more unpredictable things gets.

MAD mutually assured destruction is what kept the soviets and the west attacking, like Kennedy said we Al breathe the same air we all cherish our childrens futures and we are all mortal‚Ä¶‚Ä¶but what if your enemy doesn‚Äôt care about living we‚Äôve seen plenty of that recently with suicide bombers.

author: jimmy2k4o
text:
Like Oppenheimer, created a bomb the side of a couch that can destroy a city, he ended the worse war in human history and kept the world in relative peace since then.

Why was there not a world war 3 between nato and ussr? Why was the cold war ‚Äúcold‚Äù?

Nuclear weapons.

An evil invention that is absolutely necessary, it‚Äôs kept the world at peace for 78 years.

For generations kings/presidents/dictators etc have sent soldiers to die by the thousands for their own grandeur. They knew the war would never endanger them or their families, they were safe. Then nuclear weapons made it that nobody was safe, no king/president/dictator could survive a direct nuclear strike, and they‚Äôd be a primary target.

Now the world leaders have a deterrent against starting wars, because they know they‚Äôll be killed too along with all the lower classes.

IT‚Äôs a choice, A) risk nuclear annihilation, small risk.
B) risk the likelihood of a old fashioned war like we had before nukes.

I choose A

author: Stipe
text:
I'm curious as to what film will Nolan do next. Including Oppenheimer, Nolan's directed 12 pictures. I've noticed these 12 flicks can be organised into 4 different trilogies.

1. Let's adress the elephant in the room first - The Dark Knight trilogy. It's the only official trilogy Nolan has ever made.

2. Low budget psychological trilogy - The Following, Memento and Insomnia all follow the protagonists with certain psychological issues and deal with crime. They're really dark and grounded. Unsurprisingly, these 3 happen to be the very first 3 films he's ever made before he started doing more action oriented stuff.

3. High-concept action trilogy - Inception, Interstellar and Tenet create a unique atmosphere for the viewers. They all introduce complicated concepts or explore the existing ones (general relativity and quantum mechanics).

4. Period piece trilogy - The Prestige, Dunkirk and Oppenheimer are all set in time periods way before the time of the films themselves being released. Be it late 19th century or 1940s, they evoke historical periods and give the viewers a taste of different times, albeit The Prestige goes for a more fantastic and fictitious approach, as opposed to grounded and real-life inspired nature of Dunkirk and Oppenheimer; Dunkirk is an action film, whereas the other two aren't; finally, Oppenheimer is the odd man out by being a biopic. Still, they share a lot.

With these 4 complete, I'm curious if Nolan will add another one to some of the existing ones or do something totally different.

author: Jodi Weinstein
text: I have known off Oppenheimer's  life many years ago.  At the end of  the movie , I am hopeful that it leaves us in a very emotional state.  With that being said, that would open the door for a powerful message right before the credits run .  Example would be, "Today there are over 11,000 Nuclear weapons with the power greater than xv and z.  If we do not act now and so on, " This would hit people hard.  I am a child of the early 70s and old enough to remember 1983 and the terrifying events that led us to the closest we ever came.  Then, on November 21st, 1983 , The day after.  Made for TV movie that broke the record of most turned in.  This movie was so terrifying that it left Ronald Reagan depressed and changed his stance on nuclear war and led to some of the greatest reduction in nuclear weapons. Sadly, they are all but a memory.  If we don't do something now, the world will be a memory.  The second message the movie should have that we imagine in our heads and not on the screen is that we are at the point in the year of 1945 right before the trinity test but with AI.  Will we not learn from our mistakes.  I am afraid that answer is no.

author: Buddy villa
text: I wrote my Masters Thesis on ‚Äú Atomic Diplomacy ‚Äú about the same time the film Fatman and Little Boy came out‚Äù. It had Paul Newman as General Groves and Dwight Schultz as Robert Oppenheimer. The film also co- starred Laura Dern and John Cusack. So this film covers the same ground. Gar Alperovitz wrote the book ‚ÄúAtomic Diplomacy‚Äù around 1965. It was his term not mine and is very appropriate to these events. The development of the Atomic Bomb and its subsequent use at Hiroshima and Nagasaki. We‚Äôre the bombs used for strictly military purposes?? To bring a swift end to the war and save hundreds of thousands of USA casualties. Or was  there other motivation s send a message to the Soviet Union??  Many in President Harry Truman‚Äôs cabinet felt that just a declaration of War by the Soviet Union ( which was imminent might bring Japan to capitulate. Also leaders in Japan were sending peace overtures to the US Government through the Swedish Legation   Anyhow Gar Alperovitz laid it all out perfectly much better than I ever could in his book‚Äù Atomic Diplomacy ‚Äú. Originally published 1966 and reissued 1985 when I first read it.

author: Yvette Rodriguez
text:
First time seeing the trailer and this to me is not that interesting. Sure it's gonna have a few intense moments but overall, it's gonna be 3 hours of them talking about developing the atomic bomb and then seeing the aftermath. And that's it. Yeah, no thanks.

These kinds of movies with lots of dialogue just bore me make me lose interest very quickly. I'm more into action movies.

At the moment, Mission Impossible: Dead Reckoning Part One is looking to be the fun one that I'm most excited about. Followed by Martin Scorsese's Killers of the Flower Moon. That one is gonna be a tearjerker for sure. Heavy topics like racism, violence/brutality, injustices etc.

Oppenheimer has got nothing on these two films. The only positive things I can say I liked were the scenic shots of the desert/ land. I liked the color that was used to film this. I don't know why but it kinda reminded me of the tv show Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.

Again, this is just my opinion. Can't wait to hear what the audience thought about it when it comes out in theaters.

author: Avanish Vyas
text:
Oppenheimer later recalled that, while witnessing the explosion, he thought of a verse from a Hindu holy book, the Bhagavad Gita:

"We knew the world would not be the same. A few people laughed, a few people cried. Most people were silent. I remembered the line from the Hindu scripture, the Bhagavad Gita; Vishnu is trying to persuade the Prince that he should do his duty and, to impress him, takes on his multi-armed form and says, 'Now I am become Death, the destroyer of worlds.' I suppose we all thought that, one way or another."

text: This film makes me sick. Sure tell everyone now about the atomic arms race but forget to tell everyone how every single US General was against their deployment in the 2nd World War against Japan. Forget the fact the US purposefully targeted two non-military civilian cities and this committed one of the very worst war crimes of the 20th Century. Not 1 single US General supported using atomic weapons on the Japanese - go read the official public records of the US. It‚Äôs on military and public record. Even the President was unsure, unfortunately he listened to one of his zealous secretaries who was adamant that until atomic weapons were used their political utility couldn‚Äôt be fully realised. Perhaps that was true. Burning 100,000‚Äôs of civilians and children alive, as their skin melted off their bodies - perhaps that had political value - but that does not distract from the truth that it was also a disgusting god awful display of a war crime that every American ought to be utterly ashamed of. Imagine today the US targeting a major city of civilians and exterminating them in seconds? Do you really think you‚Äôd believe you were the champions of the free world still? Because that‚Äôs exactly what happened in 1945, twice, across two different cities. Go visit these places and I promise you you;d never ever glamorise atomic weapons again.

author: Jason S
text:
Only one nation has ever used nuclear weapons in warfare: the United States.

During World War II, the United States dropped two atomic bombs on Japan. The first bomb, named "Little Boy," was dropped on the city of Hiroshima on August 6, 1945, and the second bomb, "Fat Man," was dropped on Nagasaki on August 9, 1945. These bombings led to the deaths of an estimated 200,000 people, many of them civilians, from the initial explosions and the subsequent effects of radiation.

author: DuckAllMigthy
text: "Why would we go to the middle of no where for god knows how long?". I'll tell you, to make the most defining invention in human history. No other invention in history has had a greater global impact than the atomic bomb. It is what has kept the World economy and armies in check for the last 80 years. The invention of the bomb led to the most prosperous time in the history of humankind. Without the bomb, WW 3 and 4 would have already happened. But it will also be the bomb that will end civilization as we know it. The day just a dirty bomb (conventional bomb with small amounts of fissile material) goes off either in a conflict zone, as an accident or a terror attack, is the day the World ends. It will take between 25-40 minutes for total devastation. In the end after the fall of civilization and the nuclear winter is finally over, billions will have died, but humanity will survive, but there will probably be less than a hundred million of us left. The choice of words by Oppenheimer from the Bhagavad-Gita is the most precise quote in history: "Now I am become death, destroyer of Worlds." Oppenheimer also said that "the physicists that witnessed the Trinity test have known sin; and this is a knowledge which they cannot lose.‚Äù Also the story of the crew of the Enola Gay, the pilot said something along the lines of: "We all returned not as men, but as death itself."

author: Karthik Chandrashekar
text:
I watched this trailer Nth time to figure out how Einstein fit here and this is what I figured out.

I think scene where Einstein is from 1939, couple of famous physicists (Edward Teller and Szilard) drove to Peconic, Long Island where Einstein was staying. They wanted Einstein to sign a letter addressed to then US president Roosevelt stating the danger of using nuclear chain reaction for potentially creating a powerful bomb by Nazis. Which later led to development of first atomic bomb through Manhattan project.

In 1947 Einstein regretted writing that letter stating the following:
"Had I known that the Germans would not succeed in producing an atomic bomb, I would never have lifted a finger"

author: Mark J Maxwell
text:
"Once you have let the genie out of the bottle you can't put it back in"
The story is a bit bigger than just the Atomic bomb.
The first nuclear reactors uranium processing the Hydrogen bomb radio isotopes for medicine.
All of these innovations would not have come about without the race for the bomb.
The start of nuclear power production and the nuclear arms race.
And nuclear waste that lasts centuries.
But a few good things also developed out of the technology thankfully. Remember this is not magic it's just science !!!!!!
In all honesty I am still surprised the human race has not wiped itself from the face of the planet with nuclear weapons up to this point in time.
This movie is a definite must see I remember watching a similar movie in the eighties.
üòé

text: And what they wont tell you about the nuclear bomb drops on Japan is that Japan wanted to surrender but keep its Emperor because they considered him a deity. Because they wanted to study the devastation. What they also wont tell you is that both the locations that the nukes were dropped on had ABSOLUTELY no military value, the one thing they both had in common was how big a civilian population they had. The Americans dropped two nuclear bombs on high population refugee locations filled with the women and children and elderly who escaped the fire bombing of previous civilian targets. Fire bombing with napalm on wooden and paper building, also being a war crime during that time. GG

author: Hi Du
text:
A national emergency arises as the Nazis have a head start in building a bomb. A secret laboratory is built to stop them.

[00:08](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=8) National emergency due to Nazi bomb threat

[00:41](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=41) A secret laboratory is connected to America's industrial might and scientific innovation.

[01:04](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=64) Scientists need family support to perform their best

[01:18](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=78) This is the most important thing in history

[01:35](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=95) Pushing the button won't destroy the world.

[01:55](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=115) A miracle ends World War II and brings our boys home.

[02:20](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=140) The world is not prepared for the power of destructive bombs.

[02:52](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=172) Truman needs to know what's next.

---------------------------------

Detailed Summary for [Oppenheimer | New Trailer](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg) by [Merlin](https://merlin.foyer.work/)

[00:08](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=8) National emergency due to Nazi bomb threat
- Detonators are charged and time is running out
- The Nazis have a 12 month head start in bomb development

[00:41](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=41) A secret laboratory is connected to America's industrial might and scientific innovation.
- Unknown information is being discussed and someone is aware of it.
- The laboratory is important and needs to be kept secure until the work is done.

[01:04](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=64) Scientists need family support to perform their best
- Building a town quickly is necessary for scientists
- Location shouldn't be a barrier for scientists with families

[01:18](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=78) This is the most important thing in history
- Importance of the event is emphasized
- Impossibility of improvising the event is highlighted

[01:35](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=95) Pushing the button won't destroy the world.
- Chances of destroying the world are near zero.
- The speaker wishes the chances were zero.

[01:55](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=115) A miracle ends World War II and brings our boys home.
- The speaker can perform the miracle.
- The world will remember this day.

[02:20](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=140) The world is not prepared for the power of destructive bombs.
- Building bigger bombs can lead to unprecedented destruction.
- Giving power to destroy themselves can have catastrophic consequences.

[02:52](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYPbbksJxIg&t=172) Truman needs to know what's next.
- Truman is seeking information about the future.
- He is looking for guidance on what to do next.

author: Jim
text:
Amarillo Daily News
July 17, 1945

Meteor Brightens Outlook
for Railway Mail Clerk

The life of a railway mail
clerk can be brightened now and then.

Yesterday morning about 5
o'clock, R. J. Pankratz, coming
in from New Mexico run on the
Santa Fe, found his mail car lit
up like times square. Rushing to
the door he saw a meteor pass
directly over the train and fall
to the ground not far away.

Upon checking at the next sta-
tion, it was discovered that the
meteor had landed near Socorro,
N.M.. causing an explosive noise
and a fair sized hole in the
ground.

author: Andrea McMaster
text: Looking forward to this in IMAX, even if the territory has been covered by PBS in Oppenheimer broadcast in 1980 with Sam Waterston as Oppenheimer (an excellent show), or Fat Man and Little Boy with an underrated Dwight Schultz as Oppenheimer, but the movie wasn't that great. As we have gotten further away from the event, we understand more today. The project was a combined effort of Britain and the U.S., with the British ticked off at us (understandably) when we didn't share the final work with them, so they couldn't build their own bomb at the time. The Germans and Japanese were both working on the bomb, but weren't close, an argument can be made that if they had combined their efforts from the start, it may have been a closer race instead of Secretariat at the Belmont in 73. Even though we have had numerous close shaves with "pushing the button", mostly by stupid mistakes, the bomb has prevented another full scale world war due to the understanding of M.A.D. or maybe just dumb luck, you pick. While the first 50 years of the 20th century saw 2 full scale world wars with essentially a very violent pause between the 2, the second half limited deaths due to war to an average of 1 million a year. Has it been worth it? I am sure we will be arguing about it for the rest of humanities time on this planet. It will be interesting to see what conclusions the movie makes at the end as to how Oppenheimer felt, he did try to stop there further use and he was not a proponent of the H-Bomb, as he felt humans could not control them. He did not regret pursuing the A-Bomb as he felt it was "Inevitable". At 2:26 that will probably be Edward Teller saying "until someone build a bigger one" which is what he always wanted to do, even before they tested this one.

author: MultiDirec
text: Why the film wont work as it is supposed to. The dialogs seem like its an end of the world situation. Currently, The world is far more dangerous and packed with immense war potential than depicted. It doesnt connect. It doesn't make us feel powerless, it only looks like a visual extravaganza with talented actors. The kick, the pulse, the tension nor the thrill works at this stage. Its nothing more than a documentary by discovery. The cinematic experience for the adrenaline rush is missing since audiences world-over have seen/heard/know more about bigger better and more dangerous bombs than this one. will be okaiesh for a Nolan film but nothing ground breaking like we expect from Nolans filmography. They all had something which we craved and anticipated and of course never before seen stuff. This is plain salad.

author: James Davis
text:
Oh please. Another anti-American propaganda film from the far left with leftist actors with the express purpose to brainwash & revise history. Without seeing it, this is probably what the premise is. Americans invent the bomb. They drop it on Japan twice. Roughly 200,000 Japanese die. How brutal! How awful. It was!
The truth was we were fighting a brutal enemy who didn't take prisoners. If they did, they were tortured & executed usually by bayonet with beheading. Look up "The Rape of Nanking". Look up the "Baatan Death March." They will try to tell you the Japanese were going to surrender before dropping of the bomb. After the Hiroshima bomb, they still didn't surrender. Months before that, we fire bombed Tokyo with 100s of B-29s. Estimates put the death toll at 100,000.
More were killed in that one night than were killed with the A bomb. Yet no surrender. Now here comes an indisputable fact. Dropping the 2 atom bombs saved 11 MILLION LIVES! 10 million Japanese & 1 million American.
Admirable Chester Nimitz was uphalled when he heard these figures.
In the 4 years Americans were fighting, close to 400,000 died in combat. And that's against the Germans & Japanese!
So 11 million would of died if we invaded mainland Japan in "Operation Downfall". Which we were going to do in the fall of 1945.
If you want to know the REAL story of Oppenheimer & General Leslie Groves, Both American hereos by the way, & the inventing of the atom bombs, Save your money. What is it a $150 for a family of four these days? There are many very good documentaries on youtube without the anti-American LIES!

author: ITTIAM
text: For those watching this video and reading the comments, please read The Bhagavad Gita (literally meaning song of the lord) to understand the full context of what Sri Krishna preached to Prince Arjuna on the battlefield and when he spoke the words quoted by Oppenheimer ("I become death, the destroyer of worlds"). Superficially seen, Oppenheimer's quote from the Bhagavad Gita may mean gloom and doom as he saw it but Sri Krishna's statement was to emphasize to Arjuna there is nothing apart from him and he is time himself and everything is eventually destroyed and absorbed onto himself, the fundamental source of everything and referred to as Brahman or God. Everything is Brahman so doer-ship is an illusion as is the manifested universe. Sri Krishna therefore reveals to Prince Arjuna that he is the unmanifested, absolute reality which is the cause for everything and therefore asks him to really know his true nature and perform his duty without claiming he is the do-er as Sri Krishna as the Brahman (the absolute) manifest, is everything, including Arjuna himself and the enemies he is fighting on the battlefield. The Bhagavad Gita is so beautiful and answers so many life questions with the greatest clarity. Here is a link to an audio book: https://youtu.be/qKgU-N8mFcc
