author: GK PRIVATE
text: I met Doctor Edward Teller when I was stationed at Vandenberg Air Force Base.  The local chapter of the AIAA was able to get him to come as a guest.  I shook his hand.  The photo of me, him, the local chapter president and me is lost.  As a kid I read all the books on the manhattan project at the Providence Rhode Island library.  Gee, as the years went by I got an engineering degree then a MS in math.  Still working in the Defense Industry.  Manhattan was just a great example of a common goal, an understanding of the objective, and the dedication to carry things to completion.  Something the current young generation understands less and less of.  I also remember the PBS production of this story from 40 years ago?  The main actor was the prosecutor on those CSI shows, sam Waterston.  1984.  He did a great job.

author: Steve Nesbit
text: Given how secrets seem to leak, people today don't realize how seriously people took this project and its security. I attended a lecture in about 1970 by someone who was a junior member of the Manhattan project. He happened to be in a meeting with Oppenheimer when Enrico Fermi walked in and wrote a number on a blackboard and then walked out of the office. He asked Oppenheimer what the number was and Oppenheimer said, "It's the amount of Uranium we need to build an atomic bomb." The scientist said he spent the next few years fearing he would be kidnapped in order for foreign countries to learn what that number was.

author: thelastholdout
text: Looks like the direction will be incredible. I wonder if they'll include anything about the ALSOS mission in this. (For those who don't know, the ALSOS mission was when the US stopped and said "wait, how far along ARE the Nazis, anyway?" A team of scientists with a military escort was sent to find out after the D-Day landings. They were originally supposed to just follow along with advancing troops, but in reality they often zipped ahead of them and behind enemy lines to capture Nazi scientists and documentation about their nuclear research. It's a really neat, lesser known bit of history.)

author: tde edfgvis
text:
Several legislators in Taiwan held a joint press conference on December 9, 2022, to support proposed legislation aiming to stop the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) from forcibly harvesting organs from living prisoners of conscience in China. Nearly 20 members of legislative bodies and human rights advocates from Europe, United States, Japan, and South Korea sent videos to support the effort to fight this crime against humanity.

The press conference was held by legislators Mr. Hsu Chih-chieh, Mr. Kuo Kuo-Wen, Mr. Chang Liao Wan-Chien, Ms. Lai Hui-Yuan, Ms. Chen Su-Yueh, Ms. Chen Jiau-Hua, and the Taiwan Association for International Care of Organ Transplants. So far 26 legislators have shown their support for the proposed bill.


Taiwan legislators Mr. Hsu Chih-chieh, Mr. Chang Liao Wan-Chien, Mr. Kuo Kuo-Wen, Ms. Chen Jiau-Hua, Ms. Lai Hui-Yuan, and Ms. Chen Su-Yueh held a press conference on December 9, 2022, one day before International Human Rights Day, to call for the legislature to take action to combat forced organ harvesting.

Fight the Crime of Forced Organ Harvesting from Living People
Mr. Hsu Chih-Chieh, one of the sponsors of the Bill of Combating and Preventing Forced Organ Harvesting, said that the entire world has spoken up against the atrocity of harvesting organs from living people, and legislators from many countries look forward to seeing Taiwan push for the legislation to fight the crime. Taiwan should do its part to prevent live organ harvesting from happening, he said.

Co-sponsor Mr. Kuo Kuo-Wen said that he‚Äôs heard about the CCP harvesting organs from living prisoners of conscience for at least ten years. Countless lives have been killed for their organs, and the issue did not get public attention until recently when forced organ harvesting from Taiwanese people in Cambodia made the news. ‚ÄúI think we are late in the legislation to fight organ harvesting,‚Äù he said. He intended to expedite the legislation by working with other political parties and the administration to prioritize the bill.

Mr. Kuo agreed to make the ‚ÄúUniversal Declaration on Combating and Preventing Forced Organ Harvesting‚Äù into law, and criminalize any involvement in the pipeline. He said that the special legislation would list various forms of the crime, and aggravate the punishment for it.

Mr. Chang Liao Wan-Chien said that because of the CCP‚Äôs connivance, China‚Äôs hospitals continued to harvest organs from living Falun Dafa practitioners against their will. He also took the forced organ harvesting in Cambodia as an example. He said if a civilized country did not take legal actions to prevent the crime from taking place, such a crime would spread to every country. He looks forward to connecting with the international community and enacting laws to stop the killing.

Ms. Lai Hui-Yuan agreed and said that the international community should work together to end this crime against humanity, and form an international legal network to exchange information and stop the atrocity from happening.

The representatives from the Taiwan Association for International Care of Organ Transplants suggested that the Bill of Combating and Preventing Live Organ Harvesting should be applied to the citizens of Taiwan (Republic of China), foreigners, and people from mainland China. Also there should be no statute of limitations (meaning no time limit during which prosecution of offenders must be done).

text:
So, will this film dare tell the truth that We knew the Nazis weren't anywhere close to a successful atom bomb a year prior to Oppenheimer's "success" but kept going anyway, partly out of a self-fulfilling prophecy of mistrust for our Soviet "allies"? For a government so adamant about ending WW2, We were in no hurry at all to collaborate with our so-called allies to get the bomb made quicker, if the concern over Hitler having it first was so great.

Or how about the fact that, for all the hand-wringing they show from Oppenheimer, it was only one Manhattan Project scientist - Joseph Rotblat - who walked away from continuing the Project in 1944 on moral grounds, when it was clear Germany was far behind U.S. development? Meh. Probably not, since I don't see anyone cast as Rotblat on IMDBü§®üòí

If this movie is another 'Pentagon Studios'-Hollywood collaborative attempt to manufacture consent among Americans that nuclear war is necessary, Nolan and the U.S. MIC can miss me with that and fck ALL the way off üò°

author: Kishan Views
text:
In a 1965 television broadcast about the moments following the Trinity test, Oppenheimer said: "We knew the world would not be the same. A few people laughed, a few people cried. Most people were silent. I remembered the line from the Hindu scripture, the Bhagavad-Gita. Vishnu is trying to persuade the Prince that he should do his duty, and, to impress him, takes on his multi-armed form and says, 'Now I am become Death, the destroyer of worlds.' I suppose we all thought that, one way or another."

J. Robert Oppenheimer (1904-1967) American physicist, known as the "Father of the Atomic Bomb"

Unbeknownst to Oppenheimer initially and everyone in the U.S. and Soviet, etc. governments that birthed the atomic/nuclear/hydrogen bomb, is that it didn't just unleash city wide destruction or potential for a global nuclear winter.

A nuclear detonation--because it happens at the quantum level....also transcends across time and space in dimensions higher than the ones we live in. It affects varied consciousness beyond of our simulacrum. Oppenheimer's speech quoting the Bhagavad-Gita about being the destroyer of worlds was far more literal than people understand. Worlds plural, not singular.

Nuclear technology was not given to us for destructive purposes, but to advance our civilization peacefully.

author: Fadingfader
text: Am I the only one uncomfortable watching this? The Japanese attacked my country, occupied it, killed my people and I still feel wrong for indulging in watching a movie about creating a bomb that killed so many civilians in Hiroshima & Nagasaki. I understand that the events after the bombing of Japan ensured peace and the end of WW2, I do acknowledge that but I still do not feel great watching the development of a weapon that ended up killing civilians. I do also understand what Japan did to Pearl harbour.. if this was told in a way where there was no indulgence in the act of bombing and killing, if the story showed that the characters were solemn when they were conducting the bombings and not celebrating the deaths of civilians then maybe I think I would be able to enjoy it. The movie quality and acting/directing looks fantastic, I‚Äôm just uncomfortable.. because I know the massive impact it has on innocent Japanese lives‚Ä¶ till today‚Ä¶ knowing that it was the war-hungry Japanese leaders who created the war.. those Japanese women, children, innocent lives didn‚Äôt. I think the discomfort also comes from knowing this film is probably going to be an awards contender‚Ä¶ bcos it looks so well made, but then it‚Äôll be a movie about a making of a weapon that killed so many innocent lives that got paraded around with trophies and confetti

author: Bushwick Bill
text: I'm grew up in Los Alamos, my family is deeply rooted in the history of that town, my great grandfather worked on the Manhattan Project. I have a grandma, who's my closest only living family left in town, she still lives in the Denver Steels, has been in that neighborhoodsince the town was a secret town. She has a piece of trinium from her dad who brought it home one day when she was a kid, it was from one of the earliest tests. Its been stashed in a hollowed out Bible for 50+ years. My brother and I burried it underneath the porch years back. My old man finished working on the first steath bomber project then began working for the labs in the mid 80's. This one time when working with radioactive materials he had an accident where his protective gloves he used to hadle the materials were cut and his hand was sliced and he received the highest dose of radiation contamination poisoning that anyone ever received while working for the government, but also survived. And during his decontamination treatment he was told he'd never be able to have kids again (I have older siblings), then I was born a couple years later. He did eventually die of cancer, but only just a few years back. I ended up receiving 500k from the government after he passed.

text: The Manhattan project and it‚Äôs periphery activities (such as uranium mining) were a disaster for New Mexico, the state for which the project was chosen. The war was practically over before the decision to drop the bomb on Nagasaki was made, it was more about competing with the Soviets to dictate post-WWII international political arrangements than it was getting the Axis powers to surrender.

author: Segio Javier Pardo
text:
the other producers: well, at least we can be sure that you won't be using practical effects for that scene, right chris?

christopher nolan: the chances were near zero

producers: near zero?

My Grandpa told me this story when he was in WWII and delivering the bomb......Didn‚Äôt see the first shark for about a half-hour. Tiger. 13-footer. You know how you know that in the water, grandson? You can tell by lookin‚Äô from the dorsal to the tail. What we didn‚Äôt know, was that our bomb mission was so secret, no distress signal had been sent. They didn‚Äôt even list us overdue for a week. Very first light, sharks come cruisin‚Äô by, so we formed ourselves into tight groups. It was sorta like you see in the calendars, you know the infantry squares in the old calendars like the Battle of Waterloo and the idea was the shark come to the nearest man, that man he starts poundin‚Äô and hollerin‚Äô and sometimes that shark he go away‚Ä¶ but sometimes he wouldn‚Äôt go away. Sometimes that shark looks right at ya. Right into your eyes. And the thing about a shark is he‚Äôs got lifeless eyes. Black eyes. Like a doll‚Äôs eyes. When he comes at ya, he doesn‚Äôt even seem to be livin‚Äô‚Ä¶ ‚Äôtil he bites ya, and those black eyes roll over white and then‚Ä¶ ah then you hear that terrible high-pitched screamin‚Äô. The ocean turns red, and despite all your poundin‚Äô and your hollerin‚Äô those sharks come in and‚Ä¶ they rip you to pieces.

You know by the end of that first dawn, lost a hundred men. I don‚Äôt know how many sharks there were, maybe a thousand. I do know how many men, they averaged six an hour. Thursday mornin‚Äô, I bumped into a friend of mine, Herbie Robinson from Cleveland. Baseball player. Boson‚Äôs mate. I thought he was asleep. I reached over to wake him up. He bobbed up, down in the water, he was like a kinda top. Upended. Well, he‚Äôd been bitten in half below the waist.

At noon on the fifth day, a Lockheed Ventura swung in low and he spotted us, a young pilot, lot younger than Mr. Hooper here, anyway he spotted us and a few hours later a big ol‚Äô fat PBY come down and started to pick us up. You know that was the time I was most frightened. Waitin‚Äô for my turn. I‚Äôll never put on a lifejacket again. So, eleven hundred men went into the water. 316 men come out, the sharks took the rest, June the 29th, 1945.

Anyway, we delivered the bomb.

author: Jayakrishnan Nair
text:
"kalosmi loka-ksaya-krt pravrddho" - Lord Krishna, Bhagavad Gita Chapter 11 Verse 22

Direct Translation (grammatically weird since it is across two time dimensions - one that of Arjuna/humans (i.e the one we are in, or what we think of as time) and the other one eternal that Krishna is from, which is transcendental and outside of the multiverse (that contains many universes such as ours)):

"[Now] I have (/am) become death (/time), the destroyer of Worlds".

The reason for the two tenses is because from Arjuna's perspective, kala manifests as death in a linear progression across his timeline, whereas in Krishna's cosmic perspective, kala is eternal time (since universal consciousness has no birth or death, and Krishna is referred to as the supreme anthropomorphic personality of Godhead, the only Swayambhoo avatar of Vishnu), which always existed, exists, and will exist. It is like Arjuna is speaking in our normal forward progression of time, but Krishna is speaking from outside human time, like from an Einsteinian 4D spacetime. That is why Kala means both death and time in Sanskrit. It is hard to properly translate to English unless you can bring in the concept of dual time dimensions as in the Gita (as well as General Relativity- where past, present and future coexist as a pseudo-Riemannian manifold).

The way I think of it is like this- suppose NPCs in a 3d game were conscious agents, and I as the real human player can interact with the NPCs. I have a time dimension that is different from the time dimension NPCs live in. If the game were like a prescripted movie, and the time for NPC to die has come, it is death for them, but time for me. And in their world, I have become death.

Depending on perspective of the subject the verse can be read in one of two ways: "Now I have become death, the destroyer of Worlds"

OR

"I am time, the destroyer of Worlds"

It is very important to note here that Krishna says this verse not as himself but as Swayambhoo Vishnu, the transcendental Vishwaroopa form that he takes on to impress Arjuna before making this statement. Oppenheimer's expertise in nuclear physics was paralleled also by his expertise in Sanskrit. A true polymath genius.

author: minnuss
text:
Only the Hollywood can make a movie about creating a nuclear bomb and then using it as some kind of heroic deed !
Many comments on here are focusing on the great acting and production value.
But this raises the question of whether such a portrayal is a reflection of a twisted and corrupted humanity. Should we really be celebrating the creation and use of weapons of mass destruction? It's important to consider the impact of the media we consume and the messages it sends, especially when it comes to sensitive topics like nuclear weapons. As viewers, we should be mindful of the values and beliefs that are being presented to us, and question whether they align with our own moral compass.

A lot of these labs are incredibly isolated and, despite valuing work life balance, they don't pay enough to truly support that now days. Pride in your mission is how they claim compensate lack of pay. You end up in the middle of basically nowhere, hot and dry, in a town where you get a discount when you ride your horse to a restaurant instead of driving. Good stuff.

author: Wyatt Noise
text:
My grandpa was on a navy ship back when the military was doing nuclear testing on our own soldiers. Him and everybody else aboard was awoken early one morning, given special eye-protection and told to stand on the starboard side and look to the horizon. He said even wearing the eye-protection, the light from the initial flash was so bright, that when he shielded his eyes with his hand, he could see the bones in his fingers through his skin.

My grandpa died of cancer, though it's fair to mention he was also an asbestos installer after his time in the military until that was phased out. Didn't really stand a chance to avoid the cancer, really.

¬ªThe book of the generation of Jesus Christ, the son of David, the son of Abraham.
Abraham begat Isaac; and Isaac begat Jacob; and Jacob begat Judas and his brethren;
And Judas begat Phares and Zara of Thamar; and Phares begat Esrom; and Esrom begat Aram;
And Aram begat Aminadab; and Aminadab begat Naasson; and Naasson begat Salmon;
And Salmon begat Booz of Rachab; and Booz begat Obed of Ruth; and Obed begat Jesse;
And Jesse begat David the king; and David the king begat Solomon of her that had been the wife of Urias;
And Solomon begat Roboam; and Roboam begat Abia; and Abia begat Asa;
And Asa begat Josaphat; and Josaphat begat Joram; and Joram begat Ozias;
And Ozias begat Joatham; and Joatham begat Achaz; and Achaz begat Ezekias;
And Ezekias begat Manasses; and Manasses begat Amon; and Amon begat Josias;
And Josias begat Jechonias and his brethren, about the time they were carried away to Babylon:
And after they were brought to Babylon, Jechonias begat Salathiel; and Salathiel begat Zorobabel;
And Zorobabel begat Abiud; and Abiud begat Eliakim; and Eliakim begat Azor;
And Azor begat Sadoc; and Sadoc begat Achim; and Achim begat Eliud;
And Eliud begat Eleazar; and Eleazar begat Matthan; and Matthan begat Jacob;
And Jacob begat Joseph the husband of Mary, of whom was born Jesus, who is called Christ.
So all the generations from Abraham to David are fourteen generations; and from David until the carrying away into Babylon are fourteen generations; and from the carrying away into Babylon unto Christ are fourteen generations.
Now the birth of Jesus Christ was on this wise: When as his mother Mary was espoused to Joseph, before they came together, she was found with child of The Holy Ghost.
Then Joseph her husband, being a just man, and not willing to make her a publick example, was minded to put her away privily.
But while he thought on these things, behold, the angel of the Lord appeared unto him in a dream, saying, Joseph, thou son of David, fear not to take unto thee Mary thy wife: for that which is conceived in her is of The Holy Ghost.
And she shall bring forth a son, and thou shalt call his name JESUS: for he shall save his people from their sins.
Now all this was done, that it might be fulfilled which was spoken of the Lord by the prophet, saying,
Behold, a virgin shall be with child, and shall bring forth a son, and they shall call his name Emmanuel, which being interpreted is, God with us.
Then Joseph being raised from sleep did as the angel of the Lord had bidden him, and took unto him his wife:
And knew her not till she had brought forth her firstborn son: and he called his name JESUS.¬´

(Gospel of Matthew - Chapter 1)

author: Erhardt Harris
text:
If the atom bomb was a national emergency,
Then I wonder what the meaning of international emergency is.
The IMF, global bank, Fed, Keynesian Economics perhaps? Disguised as Modern Monetary Theory (the implication being: inflate everything until it collapses! It'll work out!)

(Where we are now. Remember what someone said about World War 4. Paraphrased, "I know not what weapons WW3 will be fought with." Well, now we know. "But WW4 will be fought with sticks and stones."

So what's the solution in an ever-escalating age of detail and agenda?
Mises and Art Laffer. Chris Nolan, Mises and Art Laffer. Should have countered The Joker with that. Instead of IGNORING THEM.

"But If Not." Chris Nolan. "But If Not."

There but for the grace of [nothing?] go I? What an omission that was.

Well, we should have listened to Ben Stein all along, Ferris Bueller should have suffered the statists and remained in high school a bit longer in the 1980's. He didn't. So the best we got was Star Trek 7 and a false death that nobody cared for. "Bridge On The Captain" Bill Shatner wanted to joke. Well, it's been fun. No the church and the Bible are not dead, someone please tell Nietzsche, the darwinian Posthumanists, the Socialists, and the Greeks that REALITY is not LOST.

So, before the liberal documentary "Waiting For Superman" revealed the overly-inflated self-importance of our ineffective Regime School systems, there was Ben Stein's 2007 "Expelled: No Intelligence Allowed" exposing the king of the new atheists, Richard Dawkins. He didn't like what Ben Stein caught on tape. Punctuated Equilibrium, the excuse for lack of evidence, becomes Panspermia. Richard Dawkins actually stated that E.T. very well could have done it. (It, being the original intelligent design of all biologies.) BUT at the same time he conclusively rejected another hypothesis. It was DEFINITELY NOT AN ETERNAL METAPHYSICAL DESIGNER FROM BEYOND the time-paradox of infinite regress. That's impossible. Allegedly. We must have untraceable, imaginary infinite regression instead, as indicated by Dawkins. OR you could heed Ben Stein's critique - and allow it in the discourses, the politics, and the classrooms. You choose, right? How can you choose if you can't talk about it?

Or we can simply proclaim the doom of all that is, like Marx declared pre-Communist Manifesto: "Everything That Exists Deserves To Die."
Well, I would assert that is not exactly true: because eternal things exist and act with awareness - or where did ours first arise from? Accident? The complexity AND regular predictability of designs (both tangible and intangible) speaks otherwise - of a designed tangible and intangible within one shared Universe. And such must have had an even greater designer. Or it all arose by accidental chance. (Does such accidental chance resemble the universe as scientists now perceive it in 2023 with all cutting edge instruments? No. The answer to such a hypothesis of things arising from non-life to life by chance is: No. SO we therefore must assert that THE POSITIVE REALITY is indeed a metaphysical one - and that the human individual is foundationally metaphysical in nature. And to the point: No, I am not a Trinitarian, but I do believe the Bible.)

"But If Not." What is the historical significance of that phrase that helped avoid certain doom in the 1940's? Someone should ask Chris Nolan, since "everyone" seems to think he's so brilliant at theater. War is real. Nolan needs to up his games - or he is simply fighting & contending for the wrong team (that of evil and Nazi-ism, to be frank - and that is not the side of The Righteous Among The Nations). Take my Word for it. (fyi, small detail, yes I do happen to believe in Yahshua. And yes, this has been a diatribe because I have access to a "typewriter" and the internet. I hope everyone has a splendid day! Happy 7th Millennium.)

text: When Oppenheimer learnt Sanskrit in 1933, he read Bhagvat Gita in most original form citing it as one of the  most influential books to shape his philosophy of life, He said after the Manhattan project "Now i am the Death, The destroyer of the worlds." In Hinduism, which has a non-linear concept of time, the great god is not only involved in the creation, but also the dissolution. In verse thirty-two, Krishna speaks the line brought to global attention by Oppenheimer. "The quotation 'Now I am become death, the destroyer of worlds', is literally the world-destroying time,‚Äù adding that Oppenheimer‚Äôs Sanskrit teacher chose to translate ‚Äúworld-destroying time‚Äù as ‚Äúdeath‚Äù. What a trailer. i am excited to see if they've also captured the philosophical aspect of Robert Oppenheimer's life.

author: Sammy Martin
text:
In the days of the War for the World, when the Dark Armies of the New Men, Chosen in Blood, and the rapacious cruelties of the Eastern Empire threatened to engulf all that was good and true, there arose a great wizard, Oppen of the Flame. He was an alchemist who heard the rhythms of creation, a seeker of the deepest mysteries of the cosmos, and a master of the most arcane and powerful arts. For Oppen had achieved the ancient goal of the alchemists, he had secured the secret of transmutation, but he barely cared for this accomplishment, for he had discovered something far more profound.

In his studies, he had come across the writings of the arcane scholar Ein, Master of Light, who foretold the existence of a Greater Fire, a Fire beyond Fire. This secret power, not born of flame or spark, was trapped within the very substance of all material things. Oppen, driven by his insatiable curiosity, embarked on a perilous journey to find the Greater Fire. And in time, Frank the Enigma, ruler of the Kingdom of Promised Liberty, did task him with finding the Greater Fire.

In a secret tower, hidden away in the barren desert of Nev, where no living thing besides them resided, Oppen and his apprentices labored tirelessly to unlock the Greater Fire. And at long last, they succeeded. They found a way to unleash the Flame locked within the heart of all things, a sorcery so vast and terrifying that it could annihilate entire cities in the blink of an eye.

As the power of the Greater Fire was revealed in otherwordly glory, Oppen is said to have proclaimed, "I have become death, the destroyer of worlds." For he knew that he had unlocked a force that could bring about the end of all things.

The tale of Oppen of the Flame reached the ears of the Lord True Man, successor to Frank the Enigma, a ruler who now guided the forces of light in their struggle against the relentless evil of the Chosen in Blood and his dark armies. This new leader, faced with the supreme evil that threatened to consume them all, was forced to make a terrible choice. He had to decide whether to unleash the Greater Fire upon the world, to use this unimaginable horror against the darkness.

author: ubernaffa
text:
I'm extremely worried about this film. On the one hand, it looks spectacular, and I'm sure it will be an incredible cinematic experience. On the other hand, I'm not sure that Nolan is courageous enough to make a film that accurately portrays the events that led to the end of the Pacific war, and the fact that it was not the atomic bomb(s) that compelled Japan's surrender. On the contrary, they had precisely no impact on the Japanese government's then current course of action, and only increased their the urgency and pressure with which they were pursuing their then current goal. That was seeking the mediation of the Soviet Union to secure superior surrender terms to those being offered by the United States. It was only after the Soviet Union declared war on Japan that they decided to surrender, and it is probable (though, we can of course never know with certainty) that the story would have been broadly similar, if the US had not bombed Hiroshima and Nagasaki.

I have a feeling that would be too controversial of a story for Nolan and Hollywood to tell, and this trailer does nothing to dispel that worry. Even so, the film looks amazing, I just really hope it does not further the propagandistic myth that it was the atomic bomb that led to the end of the Pacific war.

author: MattGames
text: Excited for this, but it's not entirely true that they were in a 'race' with the Nazis to nuclear weapons. The Nazis did have a program, but the focus was far less intense compared to the Manhattan Project, and had no real meaningful momentum behind it for most of the war. Further to this, atomic science was chiefly considered Jewish Science, and the Nazis became much too focused on their war on the Eastern Front as the war dragged on. It's also not true that the bombs were 'needed' to win the war. 2/3 major Axis nations were defeated before any bombs were dropped, and the Japanese were blockaded, had no navy left, little to no AA to protect against the already brutal firebombing campaigns (which in Tokyo was actually more devastating in regard to casualties than any single bomb drop), and most of their army were either in China, Taiwan or Manchuria and therefore not able to defend the home islands. The bombs were a factor in the Japanese surrender, but not the only reason. The coinciding invasion of Manchuria by the Soviets was also a huge fear of the Japanese, and they wanted to surrender to the Americans having been fearful of the Soviets and how they might treat the monarchy, and not wanting to fight them since Khalkin Gol. In short, the bombs were a huge component, but they were arguably a more important instrument in dictating post-war diplomacy, and establishing the US as global hegemon, and securing US influence in East Asia at the start of the Cold War than it was significant to end the war.

author: Phil4986
text:
I am grateful the producers did not make Oppenheimer into some form of apologist before the atomic bomb was actually fired for the first time. And after the fact, he knew if it was never fired on the Japanese enemy, while a wartime imperative existed, that all nations would become entranced with the fantasy, that it was a relatively harmless device that could easily introduced into a conventional armament.
People should understand that Japan had been under a firebombing campaign far more deadly then both atomic bombs and had yet to surrender,or even sue for peace at all. In fact, it was preparing for the Great Honorable Sacrifice of it's entire population to the coming invasion by the Allied forces.
The sacrifice of the people of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, not only got the Emperor of Japan so shaken that he actually stepped forward, for the first time ever, to save his nation and his people from their own destruction but also, has so far, saved the rest of the world from a nuclear holocaust.
Unfortunately, people in power today are drunk on rewriting history and they seek to make nuclear weapons a tool for the rich to control the masses. We must never let that happen. Be they the enemy of...or...our own people.

author: Rob D
text:
"I am become Death, destroyer of worlds"
Now history has the eternal question, was it worth it? It supposedly saved millions of lives by ending the War in the Pacific early, but was it worth opening Pandora's Box? Its use directly lead to the Cold War and everything that came with that.
And would someone else have done it if they didn't? It was believed the Nazis were close to getting their own bomb back in '43/'44 - we now know they weren't even close, but the Allies didn't know that at the time, so for them the race was on.
Something to think about when you watch it. Can you watch it through the lens of today knowing the consequences of their actions or through their lens when they didn't know what would come of it.

author: Baribrotzer
text: This story was also made into an opera, Doctor Atomic, by the American composer John Adams and the theatrical conceptualist Peter Sellars. The libretto - assembled by Sellars - consisted mostly of excerpts from letters, newspapers, official missives, and more, of poetry that John and Kitty Oppenheimer read at the time, and of straightahead narration. Two different staged versions were recorded for DVDs, and excerpts from both may be found here on YouTube. It's quite good if you don't mind opera, and don't mind that it has few easy-to-remember tunes.

text: If you think all movies are made for fun, think again. There are always political objectives to achieve by some. Look at the movies produced during the Cold War, and movies produced during what is called "War On Terror" period, just for examples. So, what political messages does this movie carry ?  With tension escalates between The West ( USA, NATO and allies) and The East ( Russia, China and Allies), the glooms of a 3rd World War are forming slowly in the horizon, a war in which the nuclear weapons would be the decisive ones destroying almost entirely modern human civilization.  This movie comes to tell the survivors to remember that the man who stated it all he did it with good intentions.

author: mikalmos369
text:
Sometimes I feel that marketing will be the death of art and historical fact on film...
This film seems completely overhyped especially considering that nearly the whole story of the Manhattan Project is in this trailer and is a story that has been told a dozen times already and in some cases very well... with this trailer making it seem almost like a rip-off of some of those earlier endeavors to tell the story in particular with nothing seeming very knew about this attempt and therefore an almost pointless exercise if it wasn't for the immense historical weight and importance of these events. It is not missed on me that it is a Nolan film and therefore likely to be at least semi decent and possibly of a scale that will look really good in IMAX though I'm not so sure the story itself will really benefit from IMAX. There isn't a lot of action pieces or a large-scale image to tell except for the test explosions themselves and of course sadly the final horrific results in Hiroshima and Nagasaki. The acting in the trailer seems very stiff with Matt Damon in particular not coming across very well here to the point of feeling miscast. It also does seem by far not enough of a cautionary tale that it should be, at least as how portrayed in this trailer. It should be about the most cautionary tale that could be told, but this really feels like American propaganda at its best. Again the hype and self-aggrandizement that the trailers for this film has dripping from its every pore since the first teaser to this one does not bode well. With the film's self- titling I would imagine it is meant to be somewhat of a biographical treatise of the man Oppenheimer himself but it's clear that it's really about the Manhattan Project more than anything else which I would say makes it predictable. Heaven forbid they make a film about Oppenheimer that doesn't purely focus on the Manhattan Project. It could be that it is actually a very good film but that the marketing department needs to be taken out back and made an example of, but we won't know until we see it and are $15 and more out-of-pocket and 3 plus hours of our time to prepare to go to see and then come back that we can never get back. Nowadays I really feel like we should be able to try before we buy when it comes to Hollywood films. I am not holding my breath. Is it just me or does this almost feel like desperate marketing? The only thing it doesn't do is say in the classic style with an ominous booming voice," This summer, one man, given an impossible task that will change everything but save the world and plunge it into chaos..." in reality we know that the Manhattan Project was certainly not about one man, but about tens of thousands of people and the resources of an entire country and then some along with many collateral deaths and long-term suffering aside from the actual immediate victims themselves in Japan. Historically speaking of course a huge slap was needed to stop the misguided leaders at the time in Japan in its tracks, but I'd really like to see an epic story that told the hole unvarnished truth warts-and-all. One thing I always wondered about is why the United States didn't just explode a few of these early nuclear weapons off the coast or strictly military targets away from civilian population centers. Certainly it would have been nearly as effective and bring about the end of WWII in the Pacific. Just something to think about. Remember that Pearl Harbor( another gilded Hollywood production almost akin to a little bit of propaganda) was largely military casualties and the Pentagon and Washington had had some warnings that it was to come. Of course I'm looking at this with the hind side of History. Anyway when it comes to telling this story AGAIN... I'll just sit here and hope that we're getting a less sugar-coated version of history here but if that's the case that's not what this trailer is saying and does not make me want to go see it. I know I may seem to have a controversial opinion especially when talking about just a movie trailer but when you're talking about something like the Manhattan Project and Oppenheimer or anything to do with World War II, I don't see how you can't have a controversial opinion. Out of respect for everybody that died and the collateral damage that we still feel to this day literally across the planet, that the only thing to tell is the actual truth.

text:
Oppenheimer and Einstein met a couple of times, He talked to Oppenheimer and knew he was capable of something very destructive. Not too long later Einstein Said "I do not know what weapons will be fought in World War 3, but I know World War 4 will be fought with sticks and stones" He implied a weapon Oppenheimer was creating would create peace, but also be the end of us.

Einstein once said "It is a curse to know what humans are capable, we have only tapped into 1% what science is capable of"

When Oppenheimer finally made the bomb, he said 'Now I am become Death, the destroyer of worlds'

Einstein replied "You have created the last symphony of man. But no one will be around to hear it." Since Oppenheimer sounded like a musicians name. Einstein basically meant the noise that Atom bomb makes would be anyone in it's radius who can hear it would be dead.

Robert Serber was a former student of Oppenheimer, he continued Oppenheimer's work when he died. Robert Serber eventually created the Little boy and Fatman that nuked Japan.

author: Geordie 1974
text: I'm digging the juxtaposition of celestial, almost supernatural, forces with the mundanity of day-to-day of politics; that's a truly terrifying combination! It gets to the essential meaning behind Oppenheimer's famous quotation of the Gita's 'I am become death, destroyer of worlds'. It's like we killed God with the invention of the bomb, and supplanted him with our own absolute, awful, ignorant power.

author: Create Greatness
text:
THIS IS THE MOST IMPORTANT THING TO EVER HAPPEN IN THE HISTORY OF THE WORLD

That line by Matt Damon as Leslie Groves BRILLIANTLY captures the energy of this entire film. People don't understand or appreciate the gravity of this moment in history, what was at stake. The entire fate of the world and the entire future direction of history was in the balance.

If Oppenheimer had not been successful in winning the race to the bomb for the USA...then the world as we know it today would be VERY different.

author: R 1826
text: (Until someone builds a more powerful bomb) (Truman knows what will happen). By this time, the USSR already knew about the bomb and Stalin was not impressed by Truman's announcement at the Potsdam conference about the first detonation in 1945. The Nazis were defeated in Europe, only the Japanese posed the greatest threat, and the U.S. dropped the bomb to signify that if they did not surrender, Japan would be razed. But they would discover that the Soviets were already well advanced in developing their bombs by 1949. Thus began the nuclear arms race and the rest is history.
